    content: `President Donald Trump announced an indefinite extension of the ceasefire with Iran today, hours before the 10-day truce was set to expire. The decision came at the request of Pakistan, which has been mediating indirect talks between Washington and Tehran. "We are giving diplomacy a chance," Trump said in a brief statement from the White House. "But make no mistake — our naval blockade remains in place, and our forces remain on high alert." The ceasefire, originally brokered after the U.S. seizure of an Iranian cargo ship near the Strait of Hormuz, had been fragile from the start. Iran's Revolutionary Guard had repeatedly violated the terms by conducting patrols near U.S. vessels. However, both sides have shown restraint in recent days, raising hopes for a peaceful resolution. Pakistani Foreign Minister Bilawal Bhutto Zardari has shuttled between Washington and Tehran for the past week, presenting a framework for de-escalation. The proposal reportedly includes the release of the seized Iranian ship in exchange for Iran's commitment to halt proxy attacks in the region. Iranian Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei has not publicly commented on the extension, but Iranian state media reported that talks would continue in Islamabad next week. The United Nations Security Council welcomed the extension, with Secretary-General António Guterres calling it "a vital window for diplomacy." However, the U.S. naval blockade of Iranian ports remains in effect, and the Pentagon has kept additional carrier strike groups in the Arabian Sea. Oil prices dipped slightly on the news but remained elevated above $95 per barrel. "The market is breathing a sigh of relief, but no one is celebrating yet," said energy analyst Helima Croft. "The underlying tensions haven't gone away." European allies have urged both sides to use the extension to reach a permanent agreement. French President Emmanuel Macron spoke with both Trump and Iranian President Masoud Pezeshkian over the weekend. German Chancellor Olaf Scholz called the extension "an encouraging sign." Israel has watched the developments warily, with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu warning that Iran cannot be trusted. "A temporary ceasefire is not a permanent solution," Netanyahu said. "Israel reserves the right to defend itself." For now, the world waits to see whether the extended ceasefire can lead to a breakthrough — or whether it merely postpones an inevitable confrontation.`,
