    content: `A French UNIFIL peacekeeper wounded in last week's attack in southern Lebanon has died from his injuries, marking the second French fatality from the incident. Corporal Antoine Martin, 24, succumbed to his wounds at a military hospital in Beirut early this morning, according to the French Ministry of Armed Forces. He had been in critical condition since the attack on a UNIFIL convoy near the village of Kfar Kila on April 15. The attack, which France has attributed to Hezbollah fighters, also killed Sergeant Pierre Laurent, 31, and wounded three other French soldiers. It was the deadliest single attack on UNIFIL since 2015. French President Emmanuel Macron expressed "profound sadness and outrage" in a statement from the Élysée Palace. "France will not forget the sacrifice of these soldiers who gave their lives for peace," Macron said. "Those responsible will be held accountable." The attack occurred despite an ongoing 10-day ceasefire between Israel and Lebanon, which was brokered by the United States and France after weeks of cross-border fighting. Hezbollah has denied responsibility, but U.S. and Israeli intelligence have reportedly intercepted communications linking the attack to the group's elite Radwan Force. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu offered condolences to France and reiterated his government's position that Hezbollah must be pushed away from the border. "This is what Israel has been facing for years," Netanyahu said. "Hezbollah is a terrorist organization that targets anyone — including peacekeepers." UNIFIL, the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon, has been operating in southern Lebanon since 1978. Its mandate is to monitor the cessation of hostilities and assist the Lebanese military in maintaining security. But the force has often found itself caught between Hezbollah and Israeli forces. Following the attack, France has called for an emergency session of the UN Security Council to discuss strengthening UNIFIL's mandate and resources. French Foreign Minister Jean-Noël Barrot said the attack "demonstrates the urgent need for the Lebanese state to assert its authority over all of its territory." Lebanon's caretaker prime minister, Najib Mikati, condemned the attack and offered condolences to France. But he stopped short of blaming Hezbollah, which holds significant political power in Lebanon. The incident has renewed debate in Europe about the effectiveness of UN peacekeeping missions. Italian Prime Minister Giorgia Meloni, whose country also contributes troops to UNIFIL, called for a "fundamental reassessment" of the mission's rules of engagement. Meanwhile, families of the fallen soldiers have called for justice. "My son went to Lebanon to keep the peace," said Marie Martin, mother of Corporal Martin. "He was not supposed to come home in a coffin. Someone must answer for this."`,
