    content: `United Nations Human Rights Chief Volker Türk has called for an immediate moratorium on the death penalty in Singapore after eight people have been executed for drug offenses so far in 2026. The executions, all carried out by hanging, have drawn sharp international criticism and renewed debate about the city-state's tough drug laws. "The death penalty has no place in any justice system, and its application for drug offenses is particularly concerning," Türk said in a statement from Geneva. "I urge the Singaporean government to establish an immediate moratorium with a view to abolishing capital punishment entirely." The eight executed individuals include six Singaporean citizens and two foreign nationals. Their offenses ranged from trafficking small amounts of heroin and methamphetamine to larger-scale distribution operations. In 2025, Singapore executed 15 people, 17 of whom had drug-related convictions. Singapore's Ministry of Home Affairs defended the executions in a statement, saying the death penalty has been "a powerful deterrent" against drug trafficking. "Singapore's approach to drugs is zero tolerance because drugs destroy lives, families, and communities," the statement read. "The vast majority of Singaporeans support this approach." Human rights organizations have long criticized Singapore's mandatory death penalty for certain drug offenses. Amnesty International's regional director, Rachel Chhoa-Howard, called the recent executions "a horrific escalation." "Singapore is executing people at a rate we haven't seen in decades," Chhoa-Howard said. "These are not violent criminals. Many are low-level couriers or addicts." The European Union has expressed concern about the executions and is considering diplomatic measures. The European Parliament passed a resolution last month condemning Singapore's use of the death penalty. The United States has also expressed concern but has stopped short of imposing sanctions. A State Department spokesperson said the U.S. "respects Singapore's sovereignty but urges restraint in the application of capital punishment." Singapore's legal system has been under increased international scrutiny since the 2023 execution of a Malaysian national with intellectual disabilities. That case drew widespread condemnation and led to a review of Singapore's legal safeguards. The Singaporean government has rejected calls to abolish the death penalty, arguing that it is a matter of domestic law and public will. A 2024 government survey found that 73 percent of Singaporeans supported the death penalty for serious drug offenses. Legal experts note that Singapore's use of the death penalty is not limited to drug offenses. The country also retains capital punishment for murder and certain firearms offenses. However, drug offenses account for the vast majority of executions. Families of those executed have spoken out against the policy. "My brother was not a kingpin," said a woman whose brother was executed last month. "He was a young man who made a terrible mistake. He did not deserve to die."`,
