    id: "world-uk-smoking-ban-approved-0422",
    title: "UK Approves Lifetime Smoking Ban for Anyone Born After 2008 in Historic Vote",
    excerpt: "Both houses of Parliament pass landmark bill creating 'smoke-free generation' and phasing out tobacco sales.",
    category: "World",
    author: "Mehedi Redoy",
    date: "April 22, 2026",
    time: "Hot",
    image: "https://pbs.twimg.com/card_img/2046852769219571712/PtSBaMOx?format=jpg&name=orig",
    content: `Both chambers of Britain's Parliament approved a landmark bill today banning anyone born after January 1, 2009 from buying cigarettes during their lifetime, creating what health officials call the world's first "smoke-free generation." The bill, which passed the House of Commons last week and received Royal Assent this morning, makes it illegal to sell tobacco products to anyone born after the cutoff date. The penalty for retailers who violate the ban is a fine of up to £10,000 and possible imprisonment. Health minister Wes Streeting called the vote "a historic moment for the nation's health." "This is not about taking away choices from current smokers," Streeting said in Parliament. "It is about protecting future generations from a lifetime of addiction and disease. Smoking is the single most preventable cause of death in the United Kingdom, and this bill will save hundreds of thousands of lives." The bill was a flagship policy of Prime Minister Keir Starmer's Labour government, which campaigned on a platform of public health reform. It passed with cross-party support despite opposition from libertarian-leaning Conservatives and some Labour backbenchers. Critics of the bill have argued that it infringes on personal freedoms and creates a two-tier system where some adults can legally buy cigarettes while others cannot. "This is the nanny state on steroids," said Conservative MP Jacob Rees-Mogg. "It is not the role of government to dictate every personal choice." The tobacco industry has also opposed the bill, warning that it will fuel a black market for cigarettes. Imperial Brands, one of the UK's largest tobacco companies, called the ban "unenforceable and counterproductive." Public health experts have welcomed the legislation. The Royal College of Physicians called it "the most significant public health measure in a generation." Cancer Research UK said the bill would "accelerate the end of smoking" in Britain. Smoking rates in the UK have been declining for decades, falling from 45 percent of adults in the 1970s to approximately 13 percent today. However, smoking remains the leading cause of preventable death, accounting for about 75,000 deaths annually in England alone. The new law will be phased in gradually. Starting in 2027, retailers will be required to check the age of anyone attempting to buy tobacco products. Those born after January 1, 2009 will be refused service. The bill does not criminalize smoking itself or possession of tobacco products. Those who are already legal smokers will continue to be able to buy cigarettes. The government has also allocated additional funding for smoking cessation services, including free nicotine replacement therapy and counseling. Similar legislation is being considered in other countries, including New Zealand, which passed a similar law in 2022 but later repealed it. The UK's version includes stricter enforcement mechanisms. The World Health Organization praised the UK's action. "This is exactly the kind of bold policy needed to achieve a tobacco-free world," said WHO Director-General Dr. Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus.`,
