    image: "https://www.politico.eu/cdn-cgi/image/width=1160,height=773,quality=80,onerror=redirect,format=auto/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/21/GettyImages-72953223.jpg",
    content: `Ukraine has restarted oil transit through the Druzhba pipeline to Hungary and Slovakia after a Russian strike damaged the critical route in January, Ukrainian energy officials announced today. The resumption of flow brings relief to the two landlocked European countries, which rely heavily on Russian crude delivered via the pipeline. The Druzhba pipeline, whose name means "friendship" in Russian, was built in the 1960s to deliver Soviet oil to Eastern and Central Europe. The northern branch supplies Poland and Germany, while the southern branch serves Hungary, Slovakia, and the Czech Republic. The January strike, which Ukrainian officials described as a "deliberate attack on energy infrastructure," damaged pumping stations and storage facilities in the Lviv region. Repair crews worked for three months to restore the system, often under fire. "This is not just about oil," said Ukrainian Energy Minister Herman Halushchenko. "This is about Europe's energy security and Russia's attempts to weaponize winter. We will not allow them to succeed." The resumption of flow comes as Europe continues to reduce its dependence on Russian energy in response to the invasion of Ukraine. The EU has banned seaborne imports of Russian oil but has allowed pipeline deliveries to continue at the request of landlocked Hungary and Slovakia. Hungary, which receives approximately 65 percent of its oil through the Druzhba pipeline, welcomed the news. Foreign Minister Péter Szijjártó said the resumption "ends a difficult period for Hungarian industry." Slovakia, which also relies on the pipeline for the majority of its crude oil needs, confirmed that flows had returned to pre-strike levels. "This is good news for our refineries and our economy," said Slovak Economy Minister Denisa Saková. The Czech Republic, which receives Russian oil through the Druzhba pipeline but has been diversifying its sources, said the resumption "provides additional stability." The country has been increasing its use of the Transalpine Pipeline (TAL) from Italy as an alternative. The United States and European Union have supported Ukraine's efforts to restore the pipeline, providing technical assistance and funding for repairs. A U.S. State Department spokesperson called the resumption "a testament to Ukrainian resilience." Russia has not commented on the resumption but has previously accused Ukraine of interrupting the flow for political reasons. Moscow has sought to use energy as a lever in its war against Ukraine. The resumption of oil transit does not mean a return to pre-war energy relations. Europe remains committed to reducing its dependence on Russian energy, and the EU has set a goal of eliminating all Russian fossil fuel imports by 2030. For now, however, the Druzhba pipeline remains a vital artery for Central Europe's energy needs. Whether it can continue to function amid the ongoing war remains an open question.`,
