    content: `The U.S. Department of Justice has filed fraud charges against the Southern Poverty Law Center, alleging that the civil rights organization secretly funneled millions of dollars to extremist groups including the Ku Klux Klan. The charges, unsealed today in federal court in Montgomery, Alabama, accuse SPLC leadership of a "decades-long scheme to misappropriate donor funds" intended for fighting hate groups. "The SPLC presented itself as a champion of civil rights," said Attorney General Pam Bondi at a press conference. "Behind closed doors, they were bankrolling the very hate they claimed to oppose." The indictment alleges that SPLC executives created a network of shell companies and intermediary organizations to channel funds to white supremacist groups, including the KKK and the National Alliance. The total amount allegedly misappropriated exceeds $200 million. SPLC President Margaret Huang vehemently denied the allegations in a statement. "These charges are baseless and politically motivated," Huang said. "The SPLC has fought hate for over fifty years. We will defend ourselves vigorously." The allegations have sent shockwaves through the civil rights community, where the SPLC has long been regarded as a trusted institution. The organization's "Hate Map" is widely used by journalists, law enforcement, and educators to track extremist groups. "If these allegations are true, it is a betrayal of everything the civil rights movement stands for," said NAACP President Derrick Johnson. "Donors trusted the SPLC to fight hate, not fund it." The indictment alleges that the scheme began in the late 1990s under former SPLC founder Morris Dees, who died in 2024. Dees was not charged due to his death, but the indictment names several current and former executives. According to the indictment, SPLC executives directed funds to extremist groups through a series of "educational foundations" and "community outreach programs" that had no actual operations. The KKK reportedly received approximately $15 million over two decades. The SPLC has also been accused of manipulating its "Hate Map" to target conservative organizations for political purposes. The indictment alleges that the organization designated mainstream conservative groups as "hate groups" to solicit donations from liberal donors. "They were playing both sides," said a DOJ investigator involved in the case. "They raised money by fighting hate, and they used that money to fund the very hate they claimed to oppose." The SPLC's board of directors has announced an internal investigation and placed several executives on leave. The organization has also suspended all grant-making activities pending the outcome of the case. Several major donors have announced they are freezing contributions to the SPLC. The Ford Foundation, which has given millions to the SPLC over the years, called the allegations "deeply disturbing." The SPLC has retained high-profile defense attorney David E. Kendall, who represented former President Bill Clinton during the Monica Lewinsky scandal. A trial date has not yet been set. If convicted, the defendants face decades in prison and millions of dollars in fines. The case is expected to be one of the most closely watched white-collar criminal trials in recent memory.`,
