    content: `German Chancellor Olaf Scholz announced his resignation today following the collapse of his three-party coalition government, triggering snap elections scheduled for September. The announcement came after weeks of intense negotiations failed to resolve deep disagreements over economic policy, immigration, and defense spending. "I have informed the President of my decision to step down as Chancellor," Scholz said in a televised address from the Chancellery in Berlin. "Germany needs a government that can govern. It has become clear that this coalition can no longer provide that." The coalition between Scholz's Social Democratic Party, the Greens, and the pro-business Free Democratic Party had been fragile from its formation in 2021. Tensions reached a breaking point last week when FDP leader Christian Lindner resigned as Finance Minister, accusing the Greens of "reckless spending." President Frank-Walter Steinmeier accepted Scholz's resignation and announced that snap elections would be held on September 13. Steinmeier praised Scholz's leadership during "extraordinarily difficult times," including the Ukraine war and the energy crisis. "The Chancellor has served Germany with dedication and integrity," Steinmeier said. Scholz will remain as caretaker Chancellor until a new government is formed. The election campaign is expected to be fiercely contested, with the conservative Christian Democratic Union led by Friedrich Merz currently leading in polls. The far-right Alternative for Germany is also expected to make gains, capitalizing on voter frustration with the outgoing government. "Germany needs a fresh start," Merz said in a statement. "The last four years have been a lost decade for our economy. We will restore fiscal discipline and common sense." Green Party co-leader Ricarda Lang expressed regret over the coalition's collapse but said her party would fight for "climate action and social justice" in the upcoming election. "The FDP chose to walk away rather than compromise," Lang said. "The German people will have their say in September." The political crisis comes at a challenging time for Europe's largest economy. Germany has been in a technical recession for two consecutive quarters, with manufacturing output at its lowest level since 2020. The International Monetary Fund recently lowered Germany's growth forecast for 2026 to just 0.5 percent. The collapse also raises questions about Germany's role in European and global affairs. Berlin has been a key supporter of Ukraine and a leader in European defense initiatives. "A caretaker government cannot make major decisions," said a European diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. "This could create a leadership vacuum at a critical moment." French President Emmanuel Macron called Scholz to express support and urged a swift transition. "Germany's stability is Europe's stability," Macron said in a statement. The United States also expressed confidence in Germany's democratic institutions. "We have no doubt that Germany will navigate this transition smoothly," a State Department spokesperson said. Domestically, the election is likely to focus on economic issues. The outgoing government's spending plans had drawn criticism from business groups, while labor unions accused the FDP of austerity. Immigration is another flashpoint. Germany has taken in over 1.5 million Ukrainian refugees since 2022, and recent polls show growing public concern about the cost and social impact. The snap election will be Germany's first since 2021 and only the fourth in the country's postwar history. For German voters, it represents an opportunity to chart a new course — or a continuation of the uncertainty that has defined the Scholz era.`,
