    content: `The United Nations officially declared a famine in Sudan's Darfur region today, warning that 750,000 people are facing catastrophic hunger as the country's civil war continues to rage. The declaration, made by the UN's Integrated Food Security Phase Classification, marks the first famine declared anywhere in the world since 2020. "This is a man-made catastrophe," said UN World Food Programme Executive Director Cindy McCain. "The parties to this conflict are using food as a weapon of war. They are blocking humanitarian access, looting supplies, and targeting aid workers. This must stop." The famine declaration covers three internally displaced persons camps in North and West Darfur, where malnutrition rates have exceeded 30 percent and mortality rates have tripled since January. Children are dying at rates not seen since the Darfur genocide of the early 2000s. "I have never seen anything like this," said Dr. Sarah al-Nour, a physician working in a makeshift clinic in El Fasher. "Children are arriving too weak to cry. Mothers are watching their babies die because there is simply no food." The conflict in Sudan erupted in April 2023 between the Sudanese Armed Forces and the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces. What began as a power struggle between General Abdel Fattah al-Burhan and General Mohamed Hamdan Dagalo has evolved into a full-scale civil war that has displaced over 8 million people. The RSF has controlled most of Darfur since early 2024, but fighting has intensified in recent weeks as the SAF attempts to recapture territory. Both sides have been accused of targeting civilians, blocking aid, and looting humanitarian supplies. The International Criminal Court is investigating war crimes committed in Darfur, including ethnic targeting of non-Arab communities. ICC Prosecutor Karim Khan said the famine declaration "underscores the urgency of our work." The United States announced an additional $200 million in humanitarian assistance for Sudan and called for an immediate ceasefire. "The world is watching, and history will judge those who block aid to starving children," said USAID Administrator Samantha Power. The European Union has also increased its aid package, though officials acknowledged that delivering assistance remains nearly impossible. "We have the food," said EU Crisis Management Commissioner Janez Lenarčič. "What we don't have is access. The parties to the conflict must allow humanitarian corridors." Neighboring Chad, which has taken in over 1 million Sudanese refugees, is also feeling the strain. Refugee camps along the border are overflowing, and aid agencies warn of a regional humanitarian catastrophe. "Chad cannot do this alone," said Chadian President Mahamat Déby. "The international community must step up." The UN Security Council will hold an emergency session on the Sudan famine tomorrow. A resolution calling for an immediate ceasefire and unimpeded humanitarian access has been drafted, but its passage is not guaranteed given divisions among permanent members. For the people of Darfur, the famine declaration is a grim milestone in a conflict that has already claimed tens of thousands of lives. "We are forgotten," said a mother of five at the Zamzam camp. "The world has abandoned us."`,
