    content: `China has deployed anti-ship missiles on a disputed island in the South China Sea, according to new satellite imagery released today by the Center for Strategic and International Studies. The images show mobile missile launchers and radar systems on Fiery Cross Reef, one of several features Beijing has militarized in recent years. The deployment marks a significant escalation in China's efforts to project power in the resource-rich waterway, which is also claimed by Vietnam, the Philippines, Malaysia, Brunei, and Taiwan. "This is a game-changer," said Gregory Poling, director of the Asia Maritime Transparency Initiative at CSIS. "China is not just building runways and hangars anymore. They are positioning offensive weapons that can target ships hundreds of kilometers away." The missiles identified in the imagery are believed to be YJ-12B anti-ship cruise missiles, which have a range of approximately 400 kilometers and are capable of striking vessels throughout the Spratly Islands region. "These missiles can reach any ship in the South China Sea," said Carl Thayer, a defense analyst at the Australian Defense Force Academy. "They are a direct challenge to freedom of navigation." China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs defended the deployment, stating that the installations are "defensive in nature" and located on "Chinese territory." "China has the sovereign right to deploy defensive assets on its own land," spokesperson Wang Wenbin said. "We urge other countries to respect our sovereignty and refrain from provocative actions." The Philippines, which has been the most vocal claimant in recent years, summoned the Chinese ambassador to protest the deployment. "This is a clear violation of international law and the 2016 arbitral ruling," said Philippine Foreign Secretary Enrique Manalo. "We call on China to remove these weapons immediately." Vietnam also condemned the deployment, with foreign ministry spokesperson Pham Thu Hang calling it "a serious threat to regional peace and stability." The United States, which has conducted freedom of navigation operations in the South China Sea for years, said the deployment "destabilizes the region." "China's militarization of disputed features is unacceptable," said Admiral Samuel Paparo, commander of the U.S. Indo-Pacific Command. "We will continue to fly, sail, and operate wherever international law allows." The deployment comes as the Association of Southeast Asian Nations has been attempting to negotiate a Code of Conduct for the South China Sea. Talks have been ongoing for nearly a decade with little progress. "China's actions make a mockery of the Code of Conduct negotiations," said an ASEAN diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. "How can we trust them to abide by rules they are actively breaking?" Australia, Japan, and the United Kingdom have also expressed concern about the deployment. The three nations conducted joint naval exercises in the South China Sea last week, a move China condemned as "saber-rattling." The deployment on Fiery Cross Reef is unlikely to be China's last. Beijing has been steadily militarizing its outposts in the Spratly Islands, building runways, hangars, radar installations, and now missile batteries. "This is the new normal," said Poling. "China is turning the South China Sea into a Chinese lake, and no one is stopping them." For the fishermen and cargo ships that ply these waters, the deployment adds a new layer of risk. "We are afraid," said a Filipino fisherman who operates near the Spratlys. "We never know if we will be fired upon."`,
