    content: `Italy signed a controversial agreement with Tunisia today to process asylum claims in North Africa, a move aimed at reducing the number of migrants crossing the Mediterranean to Italian shores. The deal, signed by Italian Prime Minister Giorgia Meloni and Tunisian President Kais Saied, establishes processing centers in Tunisia where migrants rescued at sea will be taken for asylum screening. Those deemed eligible will be resettled in Italy or other European countries; those deemed ineligible will be returned to their countries of origin. "This agreement will save lives by preventing dangerous sea crossings," Meloni said at a press conference in Rome. "It will also break the business model of human traffickers who profit from misery." The deal has been hailed by some European leaders as a potential model for managing migration, but it has drawn sharp criticism from human rights groups, who argue that Tunisia is not a safe country for asylum seekers. "Tunisia has a documented record of torture, arbitrary detention, and violence against migrants," said Amnesty International's Italy director, Riccardo Noury. "Processing asylum claims there is not safe or fair." Tunisia has become a major departure point for migrants attempting to reach Europe, surpassing Libya in 2025 as the primary source of Mediterranean crossings. Over 200,000 people have arrived in Italy by sea so far in 2026, a 30 percent increase over the same period last year. The agreement includes €500 million in Italian funding for Tunisia to strengthen its border controls and improve conditions in the processing centers. Italy will also provide training for Tunisian coast guard personnel. "This is a partnership of equals," Saied said. "Tunisia is not asking for charity. We are asking for cooperation." The European Commission has expressed support for the deal, with Home Affairs Commissioner Ylva Johansson calling it "a creative solution to a common challenge." However, legal experts say the deal is likely to face challenges in European courts. The European Court of Human Rights has previously ruled that asylum claims cannot be processed in third countries unless there are guarantees of fair procedures and protection from refoulement. "This deal is on very shaky legal ground," said migration law expert Elspeth Guild. "I expect it will be challenged and likely struck down." The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has not endorsed the deal but said it would "monitor implementation closely." "Any arrangement that involves processing asylum claims outside of Europe must meet international standards," a UNHCR spokesperson said. For migrants already in Tunisia, the deal has created uncertainty. Thousands are camped in makeshift settlements near the port of Sfax, waiting for an opportunity to cross. "We will still try to cross," said a Sudanese migrant who gave his name only as Ahmed. "Tunisia is not safe for us. We cannot stay here." The deal goes into effect on June 1. Whether it will succeed in reducing crossings — or simply push migrants to take more dangerous routes — remains to be seen.`,
