    time: "Hot",
    image: "https://cdn.nba.com/manage/2025/03/GettyImages-2198008870.jpg",
    content: `The 2026 NBA Playoffs tipped off tonight with a pair of thrilling games as the Boston Celtics dominated the Cleveland Cavaliers 118-95, while the Los Angeles Lakers outlasted the Golden State Warriors 127-124 in overtime. The Celtics, who entered the playoffs as the top seed in the Eastern Conference, looked every bit the championship favorite. Jayson Tatum scored 42 points on 15-of-24 shooting, grabbed 12 rebounds, and dished out 7 assists. Jaylen Brown added 28 points and 8 rebounds. "We came out focused," Tatum said. "We know what's at stake. We're not taking anyone lightly. Every game matters." The Cavaliers, who finished the regular season with a 48-34 record, had no answer for Boston's balanced attack. Darius Garland led Cleveland with 22 points, but Donovan Mitchell was held to 15 points on 5-of-18 shooting. "They punched us in the mouth," Mitchell said. "We have to respond. Game 2 is a must-win." In the Western Conference, the Lakers and Warriors delivered a classic. LeBron James, playing in his record 18th playoff appearance, recorded a triple-double with 32 points, 14 rebounds, and 12 assists. Stephen Curry countered with 38 points, including 8 three-pointers, but it wasn't enough. The game was tied at 115 at the end of regulation after Curry hit a step-back three with 2.3 seconds remaining. In overtime, James took over, scoring 8 of the Lakers' 12 points. "LeBron is incredible," said Lakers coach Darvin Ham. "He's 41 years old and he's still the best player on the floor. We are witnessing greatness." James, who turned 41 in December, is the oldest player in the NBA. He averaged 26 points, 8 rebounds, and 7 assists during the regular season. "Age is just a number," James said. "I feel good. My body feels good. I'm ready for this." The Warriors, who finished the regular season as the No. 6 seed, have been dealing with injuries. Klay Thompson missed Game 1 with a sore Achilles, and Draymond Green is playing through a back issue. "We're banged up," said Warriors coach Steve Kerr. "But no excuses. We have to be better." Other playoff games scheduled for tonight include the Milwaukee Bucks hosting the Miami Heat and the Phoenix Suns hosting the Dallas Mavericks. "This is the best time of the year," said ESPN analyst Stephen A. Smith. "The playoffs are where legends are made. I can't wait to see what happens."`,
