    author: "Mehedi Redoy",
    date: "April 22, 2026",
    time: "Live",
    image: "https://bearswire.usatoday.com/gcdn/authoring/images/smg/2024/10/25/SBRS/75851309007-63-563501.png?width=660&height=372&fit=crop&format=pjpg&auto=webp",
    content: `The first round of the 2026 NFL Draft unfolded tonight in Detroit, with quarterbacks Caleb Williams and Drake Maye going first and second overall to the Chicago Bears and Washington Commanders respectively. The selections mark a new era for two franchises desperate for franchise quarterbacks. Williams, the 2025 Heisman Trophy winner from USC, was long considered the top prospect in this year's draft class. The 22-year-old threw for 4,500 yards and 48 touchdowns as a senior, adding 500 rushing yards and 10 touchdowns on the ground. "Chicago is getting a winner," Williams said after being selected. "I'm coming to win championships. Not one. Multiple." The Bears traded up to the No. 1 pick last month, sending their 2027 first-round pick and wide receiver DJ Moore to the Carolina Panthers. "We believe Caleb is a generational talent," said Bears general manager Ryan Poles. "He has the arm, the athleticism, the intelligence, and the leadership. He's everything you want in a franchise quarterback." Maye, the North Carolina product, was selected second by the Commanders. The 6-foot-4, 230-pound quarterback threw for 4,200 yards and 42 touchdowns as a senior. "Washington is the perfect fit for me," Maye said. "I'm ready to lead this team." The New England Patriots, picking third, selected Ohio State wide receiver Marvin Harrison Jr., the son of the Hall of Fame wide receiver. Harrison caught 95 passes for 1,600 yards and 18 touchdowns as a senior. "I learned from the best," Harrison said. "My dad taught me everything. Now it's my turn." The Arizona Cardinals, picking fourth, selected Alabama edge rusher Dallas Turner. The Las Vegas Raiders, picking fifth, selected Georgia tight end Brock Bowers. "Bowers is a unicorn," said ESPN draft analyst Mel Kiper Jr. "He's 6-foot-4, 240 pounds, and runs like a wide receiver. He's going to be a star." The quarterback class also saw Michael Penix Jr. (Washington) go 12th to the Minnesota Vikings, J.J. McCarthy (Michigan) go 15th to the New Orleans Saints, and Bo Nix (Oregon) go 19th to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. "Six quarterbacks in the first round," said Kiper. "That's a record. Teams are desperate for quarterbacks." The defending Super Bowl champion Kansas City Chiefs, picking 28th, selected LSU wide receiver Malik Nabers. "We're thrilled," said Chiefs general manager Brett Veach. "Nabers was a top-10 talent. We can't believe he fell to us." The first round also saw a record five trades, as teams jockeyed for position. "This was one of the most chaotic first rounds I can remember," said NFL Network insider Ian Rapoport. "GMs were on the phones all night." The second and third rounds of the draft will be held tomorrow. Day 3, featuring rounds 4 through 7, will be held on Saturday. "The draft is just getting started," said Kiper. "There's plenty of talent left."`,
    featured: false
