    content: `Carlos Alcaraz won the US Open today, defeating Jannik Sinner 6-3, 6-7, 6-4, 6-2 to complete the career Grand Slam at age 23. The Spanish sensation, who already had won the French Open (2024, 2025), Wimbledon (2024), and the Australian Open (2025), is the youngest man in history to win all four major tournaments. "This means everything," Alcaraz said after falling to the court in celebration. "When I was a kid, I dreamed of winning one major. To win all four before I turn 24? It's incredible." Alcaraz's victory was not easy. Sinner, the Italian star who won the Australian Open in 2024, pushed him to the limit. The second set alone lasted 75 minutes, with Sinner saving four set points before winning the tiebreak 9-7. "Jannik is a warrior," Alcaraz said. "He never gives up. I had to play my best tennis to beat him." Sinner, 25, was gracious in defeat. "Carlos is the best player in the world," Sinner said. "He deserves this. I'll keep working. I'll be back." The US Open final was the 15th meeting between Alcaraz and Sinner, with Alcaraz now leading 9-6. The two have developed a rivalry that many compare to Federer-Nadal or Djokovic-Murray. "This is the rivalry tennis needs," said ESPN analyst John McEnroe. "These two are going to battle for the next decade. It's going to be special." Alcaraz's victory also completes a remarkable comeback. He missed the 2025 US Open with a wrist injury that required surgery. Many wondered if he would ever return to his peak form. "There were dark days," Alcaraz admitted. "I wondered if I would ever be the same. But I never stopped believing." With the victory, Alcaraz now has eight major titles. He is on pace to challenge Novak Djokovic's record of 24. "I don't think about records," Alcaraz said. "I think about the next tournament, the next match, the next point. That's all that matters." Alcaraz's victory was celebrated across Spain. King Felipe VI called him "a national treasure." Rafael Nadal, who retired in 2024, tweeted: "Carlos, you make us all proud. Vamos!" "Rafa is my idol," Alcaraz said. "To hear him say that means everything."`,
