    content: `House Republicans today formally launched an impeachment inquiry into President Joe Biden, alleging that he engaged in influence peddling related to Ukraine during his tenure as Vice President. The inquiry, led by House Oversight Committee Chairman James Comer, focuses on Biden's son Hunter's business dealings with Ukrainian energy company Burisma Holdings. "This is about whether the President of the United States abused his office for personal gain," Comer said at a press conference announcing the inquiry. "The evidence we have gathered suggests that then-Vice President Biden intervened in Ukraine policy to benefit his son's business interests. That is an impeachable offense." The White House dismissed the inquiry as a partisan stunt. "This is not about evidence or the Constitution," said White House spokesperson Karine Jean-Pierre. "This is about political theater. Republicans have been threatening to impeach President Biden since before he took office. They are finally following through, but the American people see through it." The inquiry centers on Biden's 2016 call for Ukraine to fire its top prosecutor, Viktor Shokin, who had been investigating Burisma. Republicans allege that Biden wanted Shokin removed to protect his son, who served on Burisma's board. Biden and his allies have long maintained that he was acting in accordance with official U.S. policy, which sought to root out corruption in Ukraine. Shokin was widely criticized by Western governments for failing to prosecute corruption. "The idea that Joe Biden would risk his career and his reputation to protect his son's business dealings is absurd," said Democratic Representative Jamie Raskin. "This is a conspiracy theory, not an impeachment." The inquiry is expected to take several months and will include depositions of key witnesses, including Hunter Biden and former Biden administration officials. Republicans have already issued subpoenas for banking records and communications. "We are following the facts wherever they lead," said Comer. "If the evidence does not support impeachment, we will not proceed. But we owe it to the American people to conduct a thorough investigation." Hunter Biden has not commented on the inquiry, but his attorney has previously denied any wrongdoing. "My client acted appropriately at all times," said attorney Abbe Lowell. "He has never asked his father for any business favors, and his father has never provided any." The inquiry comes at a politically charged moment. President Biden is expected to announce his reelection campaign in the coming weeks, and Republicans are eager to damage him ahead of the 2026 midterms. "This is about the election, not the Constitution," said Democratic strategist David Axelrod. "Republicans know that Biden is vulnerable on his age and on the economy. They are adding impeachment to their arsenal." The inquiry has divided Republicans, with some moderates expressing concern about the lack of direct evidence linking Biden to his son's business dealings. "We need to be careful," said Republican Representative Don Bacon. "An impeachment that fails in the Senate could backfire politically." The White House has instructed current and former officials not to comply with subpoenas, citing executive privilege. This sets up a likely constitutional battle that could end up in the Supreme Court. "We will not cooperate with an illegitimate inquiry," said Jean-Pierre. "If Republicans want to fight this out in court, they can." The inquiry is the fourth impeachment proceeding against a president in the past decade. Donald Trump was impeached twice, and the House voted to impeach Biden's Secretary of Homeland Security Alejandro Mayorkas last year. "Impeachment has become routine," said presidential historian Jon Meacham. "That is not what the Framers intended. It is a sign of how polarized our politics have become."`,
