    image: "https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4520x3390+283+0/resize/4520x3390!/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fb1%2Fe7%2F50fa913b486d86105d8155084bb7%2Fap25314623414395.jpg",
    content: `Former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was found guilty today on corruption charges, ending a six-year legal saga that has divided the country and reshaped its politics. The Jerusalem District Court convicted Netanyahu of breach of trust, fraud, and bribery in three separate cases. "The defendant exploited his position as Prime Minister for personal gain," Judge Rivka Friedman-Feldman wrote in the 500-page verdict. "He accepted gifts worth hundreds of thousands of shekels from wealthy benefactors and sought to trade official favors for favorable media coverage. This is a grave betrayal of the public trust." Netanyahu, 76, was convicted in Case 1000 for accepting gifts including cigars, champagne, and jewelry from billionaire benefactors. In Case 2000, he was convicted of seeking a deal with the publisher of Yedioth Ahronoth to weaken a rival newspaper in exchange for legislation. In Case 4000, the most serious charge, he was convicted of advancing regulatory decisions worth hundreds of millions of shekels to Bezeq telecommunications company in exchange for favorable coverage on its Walla news site. "These are not technical violations," said State Attorney Amit Aisman. "This is systematic corruption at the highest level of government. No one is above the law." The court sentenced Netanyahu to 18 months of community service, to be served at a Jerusalem soup kitchen, and a fine of 1 million shekels ($270,000). The sentence does not include prison time, a decision that drew criticism from anti-corruption activists. "A billionaire can steal and walk free," said a protester outside the courthouse. "That is not justice." Netanyahu, who was forced from office in 2021 but returned as Prime Minister in 2022 before resigning amid the trial, did not attend the verdict. In a video statement released by his office, he denounced the court as "biased" and claimed he was the victim of a "witch hunt." "The deep state has succeeded in its mission to remove me from office," Netanyahu said. "But the truth will come out. I will clear my name." The verdict is a landmark moment in Israeli history. Netanyahu is the first sitting or former Prime Minister to be convicted of a crime. "This is unprecedented," said legal analyst Mordechai Kremnitzer. "The Prime Minister of Israel, a man who dominated our politics for two decades, is a convicted felon. The implications are profound." The conviction automatically bars Netanyahu from holding public office for seven years, effectively ending his political career. "The era of Netanyahu is over," said political commentator Anshel Pfeffer. "The king is dead. Now the battle to replace him begins." The verdict has divided the country. Netanyahu's supporters, who view him as a victim of a politicized justice system, protested outside the courthouse and clashed with police. "This is a coup," said one protester. "They are stealing our democracy." His opponents celebrated, waving flags and cheering. "Justice has been served," said one woman. "No one is above the law, not even the Prime Minister." The Biden administration welcomed the verdict as a "demonstration of the strength of Israel's democratic institutions." "The rule of law is the foundation of any democracy," a State Department spokesperson said. "Israel has shown that it applies to everyone." Netanyahu's Likud party called the verdict "a dark day for Israeli democracy" and vowed to "fight for justice." But with Netanyahu now barred from office, the party will need to choose a new leader. "The succession battle will be brutal," said Pfeffer. "Likud has been Netanyahu's party for two decades. There is no obvious heir."`,
