    content: `The Federal Reserve held its benchmark interest rate steady at 5.5 percent today, as expected, but signaled that two rate cuts are likely before the end of the year. The decision, which was unanimous among the Federal Open Market Committee, reflects growing confidence that inflation is returning to the central bank's 2 percent target. "Inflation has eased over the past year," Fed Chair Jerome Powell said at a press conference following the announcement. "The labor market remains strong. We are watching the data carefully. If the economy evolves as expected, rate cuts will be appropriate later this year." The Fed's statement noted that inflation "remains elevated" but has "moderated significantly" since its peak in 2022. The central bank's preferred inflation measure, the core personal consumption expenditures price index, was 2.6 percent in March, down from 2.8 percent in February and well below the 7 percent peak. "We are encouraged by the progress," Powell said. "But we are not yet at the point where we can declare victory. The last mile may be the hardest." The Fed's projections, released alongside the statement, show that FOMC members expect rates to end 2026 at 4.9 percent, implying two quarter-point cuts. The median projection for 2027 is 4.1 percent. "The dot plot shows a clear consensus," said former Fed Vice Chair Roger Ferguson. "The committee is ready to start cutting, but they want to see a few more months of good data before pulling the trigger." Markets reacted positively to the news, with the S&P 500 rising 0.8 percent and the Dow Jones Industrial Average gaining 0.6 percent. Treasury yields fell, with the 10-year note dropping to 4.2 percent. "This is what the market wanted to hear," said economist Mohamed El-Erian. "The Fed is acknowledging that the tightening cycle is over. The question now is when and how quickly they will cut." The Fed's decision comes amid a mixed economic picture. Job growth has remained strong, with the economy adding 200,000 jobs per month on average over the past year. The unemployment rate is 3.8 percent, near a 50-year low. However, consumer spending has slowed, and manufacturing activity has contracted for six consecutive months. "The economy is slowing," said Powell. "That is by design. We need to see inflation come down. We are prepared to maintain restraint as long as necessary." Some economists worry that the Fed is waiting too long to cut rates, risking a recession. "The lag effects of monetary policy are long and variable," said Nobel laureate Paul Krugman. "The Fed may have already tightened too much. They need to start cutting before the economy tips into recession." Others argue that the Fed should keep rates higher for longer to ensure inflation is fully vanquished. "Inflation has proven stubborn," said former Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers. "The Fed should not declare victory prematurely. They need to see sustained evidence that inflation is under control." The Fed's next meeting is in June. Most economists expect the first rate cut to come in September, though a July cut is possible if inflation continues to moderate. "September is the most likely timing," said Bank of America economist Michael Gapen. "The Fed will want to see three or four more inflation reports before acting. That puts us in the fall." Powell declined to provide specific guidance on the timing of rate cuts, repeating his mantra that decisions will be "meeting by meeting." "We are data dependent," Powell said. "We will not pre-commit to a particular path. We will adjust policy as the economy evolves."`,
