    content: `Japan's core inflation rate rose to 3.5 percent in March, the highest level in three decades, putting pressure on the Bank of Japan to end its long-standing policy of negative interest rates. The data, released today by the Ministry of Internal Affairs, exceeded economists' expectations of 3.2 percent and marked the 24th consecutive month that inflation has exceeded the BOJ's 2 percent target. "Inflation is broadening beyond energy and food," said economist Sayuri Shirai. "Services prices are rising. Wages are rising. This is not transitory. The BOJ needs to act." The BOJ has maintained negative interest rates since 2016 and has engaged in massive bond-buying programs to stimulate the economy. But with inflation now well above target, the central bank is under increasing pressure to normalize policy. "The BOJ is behind the curve," said former BOJ board member Takahide Kiuchi. "They should have started normalizing policy a year ago. Now they risk a disorderly adjustment if they wait too long." The Japanese yen has weakened significantly in recent months, falling to 150 against the U.S. dollar. A weaker yen boosts export competitiveness but also raises import costs, contributing to inflation. "The weak yen is a problem," said Finance Minister Shunichi Suzuki. "We are monitoring the situation closely. We will take appropriate action if necessary." The BOJ's next policy meeting is scheduled for next week. Most economists expect the central bank to raise interest rates for the first time in 17 years, ending the negative rate policy. "A rate hike is almost certain," said economist Mari Iwashita. "The only question is whether they go to zero or positive. Either way, it will be a historic moment." A rate hike would have significant implications for global financial markets. Japan is the world's largest creditor nation, and Japanese investors hold trillions of dollars in foreign bonds. A rise in Japanese rates could trigger a repatriation of capital, pushing up global yields. "This is the last shoe to drop," said global strategist David Roche. "All the other major central banks have hiked rates. The BOJ is the final holdout. When they move, markets will react." The BOJ has signaled that it will move cautiously, emphasizing that any rate hike will be gradual and that the central bank will continue to support the economy. "We are not embarking on a tightening cycle," said BOJ Governor Kazuo Ueda. "We are simply moving away from an extraordinary policy that has served its purpose. Accommodative conditions will remain." The Japanese economy has shown signs of improvement in recent months. GDP grew at an annual rate of 2 percent in the fourth quarter of 2025, and the labor market is the tightest in decades. "The economy is finally emerging from decades of stagnation," said economist Jesper Koll. "This is a positive development. The BOJ should be normalizing policy." But some economists worry that a rate hike could derail the recovery. "The Japanese economy is fragile," said economist Nobuyasu Atago. "Consumers are still struggling with higher prices. A rate hike could tip the economy back into recession."`,
