    image: "https://images.wsj.net/im-35535158?width=700&height=453",
    content: `UBS today announced that it has completed the integration of Credit Suisse, the former rival it was forced to acquire in a government-brokered rescue in 2023. The integration, which took three years, involved cutting 20,000 jobs, consolidating technology systems, and merging branches. "This was a massive undertaking," said UBS CEO Sergio Ermotti. "We have integrated two of the world's largest wealth managers. It was complex, it was painful, but it is done. UBS is now stronger than ever." The combined entity has $5 trillion in invested assets and 100,000 employees worldwide. It is the largest wealth manager in the world, with a significant lead over its closest competitors. "UBS is a behemoth," said banking analyst Kian Abouhossein. "No other wealth manager comes close. They have critical mass, they have scale, and they have a dominant position in their home market of Switzerland." The integration was not without challenges. Credit Suisse's investment banking operations were significantly downsized, and many of its most profitable businesses were sold or shuttered. "Credit Suisse was a mess," said Ermotti. "We had to clean house. That meant shutting down businesses that were not profitable or not strategic. It was not easy, but it was necessary." The job cuts affected employees in Switzerland, the United States, the United Kingdom, and Asia. UBS offered generous severance packages and outplacement services, but the cuts were still painful. "Losing your job is never easy," said a former Credit Suisse banker who was laid off. "But UBS was fair. They gave us time to find new roles. I can't complain." The Swiss government, which orchestrated the rescue of Credit Suisse, has been closely monitoring the integration. The government was concerned that a disorderly failure of Credit Suisse could have destabilized the Swiss financial system. "The integration has been a success," said Swiss Finance Minister Karin Keller-Sutter. "UBS has delivered on its commitments. The Swiss financial system is stable." The combined bank faces ongoing legal risks. Credit Suisse was involved in a number of scandals before its collapse, including the Archegos Capital blowup and the Greensill Capital collapse. UBS has set aside $5 billion to cover potential litigation costs. "The legal risks are not trivial," said analyst Andrew Coombs. "But UBS has deep pockets. They can afford to pay." UBS's stock price has risen 40 percent since the acquisition was announced, as investors have gained confidence in the integration. The bank's return on equity, a key measure of profitability, was 15 percent in 2025. "This acquisition has been a success," said shareholder activist Hans-Peter Zehnder. "UBS has created value. The critics were wrong." The integration of Credit Suisse marks the end of an era in Swiss banking. Credit Suisse, which was founded in 1856, was once one of the most prestigious banks in the world. Its collapse was a national trauma. "Credit Suisse was part of Switzerland's identity," said historian Jakob Tanner. "Losing it was a blow. But UBS has done a good job of preserving what was valuable."`,
