    image: "https://www.reuters.com/resizer/v2/PKNIRQPG75NSDMLJ6XWHBEMMGA.jpg?auth=2d6a46c381469578b8f484f068f6e7e238c327c48d6428908846a2ed4239383f&height=1005&width=1920&quality=80&smart=true",
    content: `Global government debt has reached a record $100 trillion, the International Monetary Fund warned today, and rising interest rates are making debt service unaffordable for many countries. The IMF's Fiscal Monitor report found that global debt-to-GDP ratios have risen to 95 percent, the highest level since the Napoleonic Wars. "We are in uncharted territory," said IMF Fiscal Affairs Director Vitor Gaspar. "Government debt has never been this high in peacetime. And interest rates are rising. This is a dangerous combination." The report found that the average interest rate on government debt has risen from 2 percent to 5 percent since 2022, reflecting the global tightening of monetary policy. For countries with high debt levels, the increase in interest costs is consuming an ever-larger share of government revenue. "Some countries are spending more on interest than on education and health combined," said Gaspar. "That is not sustainable. They need to act." The countries most at risk are those with high debt levels and weak economic growth. Italy, which has a debt-to-GDP ratio of 140 percent, is particularly vulnerable. Japan, which has a debt-to-GDP ratio of 260 percent, is less vulnerable because most of its debt is held domestically and interest rates remain low. "Japan is an exception," said Gaspar. "Most countries are not Japan. They cannot rely on captive domestic investors." The United States, which has a debt-to-GDP ratio of 120 percent, is not at immediate risk of a debt crisis because the dollar is the world's reserve currency. But the IMF warned that the US fiscal trajectory is unsustainable. "The United States cannot continue borrowing at this pace indefinitely," said Gaspar. "At some point, investors will lose confidence. The consequences would be catastrophic." The IMF called on governments to take action to reduce debt levels, including cutting spending, raising taxes, and implementing structural reforms to boost growth. "There is no magic solution," said Gaspar. "Countries need to make difficult choices. The longer they wait, the harder it will be." The report also highlighted the risks posed by China's rising debt levels. China's government debt has increased from 40 percent of GDP in 2015 to 80 percent of GDP today, and the country's local government debt is even higher. "China's debt is a concern," said Gaspar. "The country's growth is slowing, and its financial system is fragile. A crisis in China would have global implications." The IMF's warning comes as finance ministers and central bankers gather in Washington for the spring meetings of the IMF and World Bank. Debt is expected to be a major topic of discussion. "We cannot kick the can down the road forever," said World Bank President Ajay Banga. "The debt problem needs to be addressed. We need to work together to find solutions." Some economists argue that the IMF's warnings are overblown. "Debt is not a problem as long as interest rates are below growth rates," said economist Stephanie Kelton. "And right now, growth is higher than interest rates in most countries." But others worry that the global economy is sleepwalking into a crisis. "The parallels to 2008 are eerie," said economist Nouriel Roubini. "Everyone knows there is a problem, but no one wants to be the first to act. That is how crises happen."`,
