    content: `On June 15, 1859, an American farmer named Lyman Cutlar shot a pig that was rooting in his potato garden. That pig belonged to a British employee named Charles Griffin. The pig's death nearly triggered a war between the United States and Great Britain. "It sounds absurd," said historian Dr. Mike Vouri. "Two great powers nearly went to war over a pig. But the pig was just the spark. The real issue was the border between the United States and British North America." The San Juan Islands, located between Vancouver Island and the Washington Territory, were claimed by both nations. The Oregon Treaty of 1846 had established the border at the 49th parallel, but it left the San Juan Islands in dispute. "The treaty was ambiguous," said Vouri. "It said the border would follow 'the deepest channel' between the mainland and Vancouver Island. But there were two channels. The Americans thought they owned the islands. The British thought they did." The pig was the trigger. After Cutlar shot the pig, British authorities threatened to arrest him. American settlers called for military protection. Brigadier General William Harney, the American commander in Oregon, dispatched 66 soldiers to San Juan Island. "Harney was a hothead," said Vouri. "He wanted a war with Britain. He saw the pig as a pretext." The British responded by sending three warships and 1,000 marines. The Americans reinforced their position with additional troops. For several months, the two sides faced off on San Juan Island. "It was a standoff," said Vouri. "The British had the naval advantage. The Americans had the advantage of position. Neither side wanted to fire the first shot." The situation was defused by cooler heads in Washington and London. President James Buchanan dispatched General Winfield Scott to negotiate a truce. The British agreed to a joint military occupation of the island. "Scott was a diplomat as well as a general," said Vouri. "He calmed tensions and bought time for negotiations." The dispute was eventually resolved by international arbitration. In 1872, Kaiser Wilhelm I of Germany ruled in favor of the United States, awarding the San Juan Islands to America. "The pig had a name," said Vouri. "It was called the Pig War. But it wasn't about the pig. It was about sovereignty, pride, and the unfinished business of the Oregon Treaty." The Pig War has no casualties — except the pig. "One pig died," said Vouri. "That's the only casualty. It's probably the most peaceful war in history." Today, the San Juan Islands are part of Washington State. The joint military occupation is commemorated at the San Juan Island National Historical Park. "It's a reminder that wars can be avoided," said Vouri. "The Pig War ended with a whimper, not a bang. That's something to celebrate."`,
