    content: `In 1837, a failed civil service examinee named Hong Xiuquan had a vision. He saw an old man with a golden beard who told him that humanity was worshipping demons. The old man, Hong believed, was God the Father. Hong was the younger brother of Jesus Christ. His mission: to establish the Kingdom of Heavenly Peace on Earth. The Taiping Rebellion (1850-1864) was the bloodiest civil war in human history. By the time the Qing government suppressed it, an estimated 20 to 30 million people had died — more than the death toll of World War I. "It's one of the most understudied events in world history," said historian Dr. Jonathan Spence. "The Taiping Rebellion was a cataclysm. It reshaped China. It killed millions. And yet most people in the West have never heard of it." Hong's followers, known as the Taiping, were a strange blend of Christianity, Confucianism, and Chinese folk religion. They rejected the Qing dynasty, which they considered illegitimate. They called for land redistribution, gender equality, and the abolition of foot-binding and opium. "Hong was a visionary," said Spence. "He was also mentally ill. His theology was incoherent. His policies were contradictory. But he inspired millions of people to follow him." The Taiping captured Nanjing in 1853 and made it their capital. They controlled much of southern and central China for more than a decade. The Qing government, weakened by corruption and inefficiency, struggled to respond. "The Qing were on the verge of collapse," said Spence. "Only the intervention of Western powers saved them." The British and French, who had their own commercial interests in China, eventually sided with the Qing. They supplied weapons, training, and even troops. The Taiping were defeated in 1864, when Nanjing fell after a brutal siege. Hong had died of poison months earlier, believing that God would rescue him. "He waited for a divine intervention that never came," said Spence. "When it became clear that God was not going to save him, he took his own life." The Taiping Rebellion had profound consequences for China. The Qing government, though victorious, was fatally weakened. The death toll devastated the population. The economy was shattered. "The rebellion set the stage for the fall of the Qing dynasty in 1911," said Spence. "It also exposed the weakness of China to the Western powers. The era of foreign domination was about to begin." The Taiping Rebellion is remembered in China as a tragedy. Hong Xiuquan is seen as a tragic figure — a man of faith who led millions to their deaths. "He believed he was doing God's work," said Spence. "Perhaps he was. But if so, God has a strange sense of humor."`,
