    content: `In 1942, a group of Polish soldiers in Iran purchased a Syrian brown bear cub from a young boy. They named him Wojtek, which means "happy warrior" in Polish. Wojtek grew up to become a corporal in the Polish army, a beer-drinking mascot who helped carry artillery shells during the Battle of Monte Cassino. "Wojtek was no ordinary bear," said historian Dr. Alexandra Richie. "He was a soldier. He was enlisted. He had a rank. He was treated like any other member of the unit." The bear was adopted by the 22nd Artillery Supply Company of the Polish II Corps. He was raised on condensed milk, fruit, and honey. He quickly became a beloved mascot. "The soldiers taught Wojtek to salute," said Richie. "They taught him to wrestle. He would drink beer and smoke cigarettes. He was one of the guys." As Wojtek grew, he became strong enough to carry heavy artillery shells. During the Battle of Monte Cassino in 1944, he helped move crates of ammunition to the front lines. "The soldiers claimed that Wojtek never dropped a single shell," said Richie. "He worked alongside them, under fire, without complaint." In recognition of his service, Wojtek was officially enlisted as a corporal. He was given a serial number and a paybook. "He was a real soldier," said Richie. "He had a rank. He had a number. He was subject to military discipline." After the war, Wojtek was demobilized and sent to the Edinburgh Zoo in Scotland. He lived there until his death in 1963. His former comrades visited him regularly. "They would throw him cigarettes, which he would smoke," said Richie. "They would feed him beer. He would wave to them. It was a bittersweet reunion." Wojtek's story has become a symbol of the Polish experience in World War II. A statue of Wojtek now stands in Edinburgh, and another in Krakow. "He represents the resilience and humor of the Polish people," said Richie. "Even in the darkest times, they found a way to smile." The bear's legacy lives on. There are Wojtek-themed beers, books, and even a video game. His story has been told and retold. "Wojtek was a bear," said Richie. "But he was also a soldier, a friend, and a symbol. He reminds us that humanity can be found in the strangest places."`,
