    image: "https://media.wbur.org/wp/2012/02/0221_GreatMolassesFlood_p32-33_300-1000x569.jpg",
    content: `On January 15, 1919, a 50-foot-tall steel tank filled with 2.3 million gallons of molasses exploded in Boston's North End. A wave of sticky syrup, moving at 35 miles per hour, swept through the streets. It crushed buildings, overturned vehicles, and drowned people where they stood. The Great Molasses Flood killed 21 people and injured 150. "It was like a tsunami," said survivor Anthony di Stasio, who was 10 years old at the time. "I heard a noise like a machine gun. Then I saw this brown wave coming toward me. I ran, but the molasses caught me. It picked me up and threw me against a wall." The tank, owned by the Purity Distilling Company, had been built hastily to meet the demand for industrial alcohol used in munitions production during World War I. It was poorly constructed and poorly maintained. "The tank was a disaster waiting to happen," said historian Dr. Stephen Puleo, author of "Dark Tide." "It leaked so badly that the company painted it brown to hide the stains. The children in the neighborhood would collect the molasses in buckets." The explosion was caused by a combination of factors: a sudden temperature increase, fermentation of the molasses, and structural weaknesses in the tank. The rivets popped like bullets. "The sound was deafening," said Puleo. "People thought it was an explosion or an earthquake. Some thought the Germans were attacking." The wave of molasses was up to 15 feet high at its peak. It knocked buildings off their foundations. It crumpled the steel girders of the elevated railway. It swept horses, wagons, and people into the harbor. "The molasses was thick and sticky," said Puleo. "People couldn't move. They couldn't breathe. They drowned in syrup." The rescue effort was heroic but difficult. Firefighters, police, and civilians waded into the sticky mess, pulling survivors from the debris. The Red Cross set up a temporary hospital. "They worked for days," said Puleo. "The molasses was everywhere. It coated everything. It took weeks to clean up." The aftermath of the flood was a legal battle. The victims sued the Purity Distilling Company, which blamed anarchists for the explosion. "They claimed it was a bomb," said Puleo. "But the evidence pointed to negligence." After six years of litigation, the company paid $600,000 in settlements — about $10 million in today's money. "It was one of the first class-action lawsuits in American history," said Puleo. "It established the principle that corporations are responsible for their actions." The Great Molasses Flood is remembered as one of the strangest disasters in American history. "It's almost comical," said Puleo. "A flood of molasses. It sounds like a joke. But it wasn't a joke. People died. It was a tragedy." Today, a small plaque marks the site of the disaster. On hot summer days, residents of the North End say they can still smell the faint scent of molasses. "It never really went away," said Puleo. "The molasses seeped into the soil. It seeped into the harbor. It's part of Boston now."`,
