    image: "https://content.api.news/v3/images/bin/2be11e5f20bb272fa09185fdf2476976",
    content: `Prague has a peculiar tradition: throwing people out of windows. The act, known as defenestration, has occurred at least three times in the city's history. Two of those defenestrations sparked major wars. The First Defenestration of Prague occurred in 1419, when a mob of radical Hussites stormed the New Town Hall and threw the judge, the burgomaster, and 13 town councilors out of the window. Some were killed by the fall. Others were beaten to death by the crowd below. "The Hussites were angry," said historian Dr. Peter Wilson. "They wanted religious reform. They wanted the Catholic Church to give up its wealth and power. The town councilors represented everything they hated." The First Defenestration sparked the Hussite Wars, a series of conflicts that devastated Bohemia for two decades. The Hussites, led by the one-eyed general Jan Žižka, defeated five Catholic crusades before eventually negotiating a peace. "Žižka was a military genius," said Wilson. "He never lost a battle. He used wagons as mobile fortresses. He turned peasant farmers into soldiers. The Catholic armies didn't know how to fight him." The Second Defenestration of Prague, in 1618, was even more consequential. Protestant nobles, angry at Catholic restrictions on their religious freedom, stormed Prague Castle and threw two Catholic governors and their secretary out of a third-floor window. "They fell 50 feet," said Wilson. "But they landed in a pile of manure and survived. The Catholics said they were saved by angels. The Protestants said it was the manure." The Second Defenestration triggered the Thirty Years' War, one of the most destructive conflicts in European history. The war, which pitted Protestant states against Catholic states, killed an estimated 8 million people — mostly civilians. "It was a religious war, a political war, and a dynastic war all rolled into one," said Wilson. "It involved every major power in Europe. It devastated Germany. It changed the map of Europe." The war ended with the Peace of Westphalia in 1648, which established the principle of state sovereignty and recognized the right of each German state to choose its own religion. "The Peace of Westphalia is considered the beginning of the modern international system," said Wilson. "It ended the idea of a single Christian commonwealth. It recognized that states had the right to govern themselves." The Third Defenestration of Prague, in 1948, was less dramatic. The Czechoslovak foreign minister, Jan Masaryk, was found dead beneath the bathroom window of the Foreign Ministry. The communist government claimed he committed suicide. His family believed he was murdered. "We'll never know what really happened," said Wilson. "But it's a reminder that defenestration is a recurring theme in Czech history." Today, the word "defenestration" is used to describe any act of throwing someone or something out of a window. But its origins remain distinctly Czech. "The Czechs have a word for it," said Wilson. "They call it 'defenestrace.' It's part of their national identity. It's how they deal with politicians they don't like."`,
