    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://www.lookandlearn.com/history-images/preview/LLB/LLB8001/LLB8001-068-06.jpg",
    content: `In 1135, King Henry I of England died without a male heir. He had designated his daughter, Empress Matilda, as his successor. But his nephew, Stephen of Blois, rushed to London and had himself crowned instead. The resulting civil war, known as The Anarchy, lasted 19 years. "It was a brutal conflict," said historian Dr. Catherine Hanley, author of "Matilda: Empress, Queen, Warrior." "England descended into chaos. Castles were built everywhere. The countryside was pillaged. The people suffered terribly." Matilda was no ordinary claimant. She had been the Holy Roman Empress, married to Emperor Henry V. She was intelligent, educated, and determined. "She had been raised to rule," said Hanley. "Her father had made his barons swear fealty to her twice. She believed the throne was hers by right." Stephen was a charismatic leader but a poor administrator. He quickly alienated many of his supporters by seizing church property and alienating the powerful clergy. "Stephen was popular but ineffective," said Hanley. "He made promises he couldn't keep. He gave away lands he didn't own. He was a good man, but a terrible king." The war turned decisively in Matilda's favor in 1141. She captured Stephen at the Battle of Lincoln and imprisoned him. She was proclaimed "Lady of the English" and prepared for her coronation. "But Matilda was her own worst enemy," said Hanley. "She was arrogant. She refused to compromise. She alienated her supporters. Within months, she was forced to flee London." Stephen was released in exchange for Matilda's brother, Robert of Gloucester. The war continued, with neither side able to gain a decisive advantage. "It was a stalemate," said Hanley. "Both sides were exhausted. Both sides wanted peace." The conflict ended in 1153, when Stephen agreed to recognize Matilda's son, Henry, as his heir. Stephen died the following year, and Henry became King Henry II. "Matilda never became queen," said Hanley. "But her son did. She outlived Stephen. She saw her son crowned. She got the last laugh." The Anarchy has been romanticized in popular culture. The civil war in George R.R. Martin's "A Song of Ice and Fire" was inspired by the conflict between Matilda and Stephen. "Martin has acknowledged the influence," said Hanley. "The Dance of the Dragons — the Targaryen civil war — is based on The Anarchy. It's a story of a woman fighting for her rightful throne."`,
