    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://i.guim.co.uk/img/uploads/2018/07/11/Header_1.jpg?width=700&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=4e39b97fca9dcab43496f1cb6e7a7475",
    content: `When we think of Bletchley Park, we think of Alan Turing. But Turing was just one of thousands of codebreakers who worked at the British mansion. Most of them were women. And most of them have been forgotten. "Women were the backbone of Bletchley Park," said historian Dr. Kerry Howard. "They operated the bombes, the machines that cracked the Enigma code. They analyzed the decrypts. They translated the messages. They did the work that won the war." The women of Bletchley Park were recruited from universities, from the military, from civilian life. They were mathematicians, linguists, classics scholars. They were sworn to secrecy. "They couldn't tell anyone what they were doing," said Howard. "Not their parents. Not their husbands. Not their children. Many took the secrets to their graves." The most famous female codebreaker at Bletchley Park was Mavis Batey. She broke the Italian naval code in 1941, providing intelligence that helped the Royal Navy win the Battle of Cape Matapan. "Mavis was brilliant," said Howard. "She could see patterns that others missed. She was one of the best codebreakers at Bletchley — male or female." Another notable codebreaker was Joan Clarke, who worked closely with Alan Turing. She was a mathematician who rose to become deputy head of her section. "Joan was Turing's intellectual equal," said Howard. "He proposed marriage to her. She turned him down. She later said she loved him, but not in that way." In the United States, women also worked as codebreakers. The US Navy's WAVES (Women Accepted for Volunteer Emergency Service) program trained thousands of women to intercept and decrypt Japanese communications. "The WAVES were essential," said Howard. "They broke the Japanese naval code. They tracked the Japanese fleet. They helped win the Battle of Midway." After the war, the women codebreakers returned to civilian life. They were not celebrated. They were not honored. They were told to forget. "The secrecy was absolute," said Howard. "The codebreakers were warned that revealing their work was a crime. They took their secrets to the grave." In recent years, historians have begun to recognize the contributions of women codebreakers. Bletchley Park has opened exhibits honoring them. Books and documentaries have told their stories. "It's time to give them the credit they deserve," said Howard. "They were geniuses. They won the war. They saved lives. We owe them a debt of gratitude."`,
