    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://www.onthisday.com/images/photos/spanish-flu.jpg",
    content: `The 1918 influenza pandemic killed an estimated 50 to 100 million people worldwide — more than the total killed in World War I. It infected one-third of the global population. It killed more people in a single year than the Black Death killed in a century. And yet it has been largely forgotten. "The pandemic was overshadowed by the war," said historian Dr. Laura Spinney, author of "Pale Rider." "People were exhausted. They wanted to move on. They wanted to forget. So they did." The pandemic began in the spring of 1918. The first cases were reported at a military base in Kansas. Within months, the virus had spread to Europe, Asia, Africa, and the Americas. "The war helped spread the virus," said Spinney. "Soldiers on troop ships were packed together. They carried the virus from one continent to another. The pandemic followed the war." The 1918 flu was unusual. It killed young, healthy adults, not just the elderly and the sick. The virus triggered a "cytokine storm," an overreaction of the immune system that destroyed the lungs. "People died within days," said Spinney. "They developed pneumonia. They turned blue. They drowned in their own fluids. It was a horrible way to die." The pandemic had profound social and economic consequences. Schools, theaters, and churches closed. Funerals were banned. Bodies piled up in morgues. "The pandemic was a global trauma," said Spinney. "It changed the way people thought about health, about government, about each other." The pandemic also influenced the arts. The Surrealist movement, with its focus on death and the irrational, emerged in the aftermath. The poetry of T.S. Eliot and the novels of Virginia Woolf were shaped by the pandemic. "Artists were trying to make sense of the senseless," said Spinney. "The pandemic had no meaning. It was random. It was cruel. Art was a way of processing that." Despite its scale, the 1918 flu has been largely forgotten. The COVID-19 pandemic, which killed millions in 2020-2022, has revived interest in the 1918 flu. "We saw the same patterns," said Spinney. "The same debates about masks, about lockdowns, about personal freedom. The 1918 flu is not just history. It's a warning."`,
