    content: `In July 1807, Napoleon Bonaparte decided to celebrate the signing of the Treaties of Tilsit by hunting rabbits. He invited his generals and their wives to join him. The rabbits had other ideas. "It was supposed to be a relaxing day," said historian Dr. Andrew Roberts. "Napoleon was at the height of his power. He had just defeated Russia and Prussia. He wanted to celebrate. Instead, he was humiliated." The problem was the rabbits. Napoleon's chief of staff had purchased hundreds of rabbits for the hunt. But he had bought domesticated rabbits, not wild ones. "Domesticated rabbits are not afraid of humans," said Roberts. "They associate humans with food. When the hunting party arrived, the rabbits thought it was feeding time." The rabbits swarmed. They surrounded Napoleon. They climbed his legs. They nibbled at his coat. "Napoleon tried to shoo them away," said Roberts. "But the rabbits kept coming. There were too many. He retreated to his carriage. The rabbits followed. They tried to climb into the carriage with him." The great conqueror of Europe was chased from the field by a swarm of fluffy rabbits. His generals looked on in disbelief. "It was a complete farce," said Roberts. "Napoleon was furious. He blamed his chief of staff. The chief of staff blamed the rabbit supplier. No one wanted to take responsibility." The rabbit hunt became a legend. It was retold as a cautionary tale about the dangers of overconfidence. "Napoleon had conquered Europe," said Roberts. "But he couldn't conquer rabbits. It was a reminder that even the greatest men can be humbled by the smallest creatures." Today, the story of Napoleon's rabbit hunt is a favorite of historians and trivia buffs. "It's a funny story," said Roberts. "But it's also a human story. It shows that Napoleon was not a god. He was a man. And like all men, he could be undone by his own arrogance."`,
