    content: `On the morning of December 6, 1917, the French cargo ship SS Mont-Blanc collided with the Norwegian vessel SS Imo in Halifax Harbor. The Mont-Blanc was carrying 2,925 tons of explosives: TNT, picric acid, and benzole. The collision sparked a fire. Twenty minutes later, the Mont-Blanc exploded. "It was the largest man-made explosion before the atomic bomb," said historian Dr. John Boileau. "The blast flattened two square kilometers of the city. It killed 2,000 people. It injured 9,000. It was a catastrophe." The explosion was heard hundreds of miles away. A tsunami, created by the blast, swept ships onto the shore. A pressure wave shattered windows 50 miles away. "The sound was deafening," said Boileau. "Survivors reported a flash of light, then a roar, then nothing. Many went deaf." The destruction was unimaginable. The Richmond neighborhood of Halifax was obliterated. Houses were reduced to splinters. Factories collapsed. Churches crumbled. "It looked like a war zone," said Boileau. "Because it was a war zone. The city had been hit by a weapon of war, even if the weapon was an accident." The explosion also caused a tidal wave. The wave, which reached heights of 60 feet, destroyed the Mi'kmaq village of Turtle Grove. "The Mi'kmaq had lived there for generations," said Boileau. "The wave swept away their homes, their canoes, their belongings. Many died." The response to the disaster was heroic. People from across Nova Scotia rushed to Halifax to help. The Massachusetts government sent medical supplies and personnel. "The Boston-Halifax connection was born," said Boileau. "Every year, Halifax sends Boston a Christmas tree as thanks. It's a tradition that continues to this day." The Halifax Explosion remains the largest explosion in Canadian history. It is also the largest man-made explosion before the atomic bomb. "Hiroshima was bigger," said Boileau. "But only just. The Halifax Explosion was a glimpse of what nuclear weapons would do. It was a warning that we ignored."`,
