    image: "https://thebeliever.net/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/tumblr_inline_obt5dnWAid1rglck1_540.png",
    content: `In early 20th-century New York, there was an unwritten rule: straw hats could not be worn after September 15. Anyone who violated the rule risked having their hat stomped. In 1922, the tradition led to full-scale riots. "It was a bizarre phenomenon," said historian Dr. Joshua Zeitz. "Young men would roam the streets looking for people wearing straw hats. They would snatch them off their heads and crush them. It was a game. But it got out of hand." The "straw hat season" began on May 15, when men could start wearing their summer hats. It ended on September 15, when they were expected to switch to felt hats. The rule was enforced by "hat-tipping" gangs. "There was no law," said Zeitz. "It was a social convention. But it was enforced with violence. If you wore a straw hat after September 15, you were asking for trouble." On September 13, 1922, the trouble began. A group of boys in Manhattan started smashing hats. They were joined by others. Soon, hundreds of young men were roaming the streets, destroying any straw hat they could find. "It was a mob," said Zeitz. "They weren't targeting anyone in particular. They were just smashing hats. Anyone who got in their way was beaten." The riots lasted for three days. By the time they ended, hundreds of hats had been destroyed. Dozens of people had been injured. The police made numerous arrests. "The mayor was furious," said Zeitz. "He ordered the police to crack down. The next year, they did. The riots never happened again." The Straw Hat Riots are remembered as one of the strangest episodes in New York history. "It's a reminder that fashion can be dangerous," said Zeitz. "People take their clothes seriously. They always have."`,
