    image: "https://addpmp.slamjam.com/media/pages/posts/amnesia/1980658769-1642607049/loadimg-400x.jpg",
    content: `In January 1962, a girls' school in Tanganyika (now Tanzania) experienced an outbreak of laughter. It started with three girls. Within a week, 95 of the school's 159 students were laughing uncontrollably. The school was closed. The girls were sent home. But the laughter followed them. "It was a mass psychogenic illness," said psychiatrist Dr. Robert Bartholomew. "The girls couldn't stop laughing. They would laugh for hours, sometimes for days. They couldn't eat. They couldn't sleep. They couldn't go to school." The laughter epidemic spread to neighboring villages. Within months, over 1,000 people had been affected. Some laughed for 16 days straight. "It was terrifying," said Bartholomew. "People thought they were possessed. They called priests. They called witch doctors. Nothing worked." The epidemic eventually subsided after six months. No one knows why it started. No one knows why it ended. "Mass psychogenic illness is real," said Bartholomew. "It's not faking. It's not attention-seeking. The people who experience it are genuinely suffering. Their symptoms are real." The Tanganyika Laughter Epidemic is one of the most famous examples of mass psychogenic illness. Similar outbreaks have occurred elsewhere, including a 1965 outbreak in a Singapore boarding school and a 2007 outbreak in a Mexican school. "It's a mystery," said Bartholomew. "We don't fully understand why it happens. But it does. And it's a reminder that the mind is powerful."`,
