    image: "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9c/Horseshoe_Brewery%2C_London%2C_c._1800.jpg",
    content: `On October 17, 1814, a vat of beer at the Meux & Co Brewery in London burst. The vat contained 323,000 gallons of porter, a dark beer. The explosion ruptured other vats, unleashing a wave of beer that swept through the streets of St. Giles. "It was a tsunami of beer," said historian Dr. Ian Hornsey. "The wave was 15 feet high. It moved at 20 miles per hour. It destroyed two houses. It killed eight people." The victims were mostly women and children. They were at home, doing laundry, having dinner, playing. The beer wave swept them away. "It was a freak accident," said Hornsey. "No one could have predicted it. The brewery was in a residential area. The vats were huge. When they burst, there was nothing to stop the beer." The victims died of drowning, blunt force trauma, and alcohol poisoning. "They were not drunk," said Hornsey. "They were killed by the force of the wave. The beer was incidental." The brewery was not held liable. The coroner ruled the deaths an "accidental visitation of God." "There was no lawsuit," said Hornsey. "In 1814, you couldn't sue a brewery for a beer flood. It was just bad luck." The Beer Flood of London is one of the strangest disasters in British history. "It's almost comical," said Hornsey. "A flood of beer. It sounds like a joke. But it wasn't a joke. People died. It was a tragedy."`,
