    image: "https://birdsofparadise.org/assets/images/no-bird-brains-poll-1.jpg",
    content: `Andrew Jackson, the seventh president of the United States, was known for his colorful language. His pet parrot, a African grey named Poll, learned from the best. When Jackson died in 1845, Poll attended his funeral. The parrot, reportedly, would not stop swearing. "The parrot had picked up Jackson's vocabulary," said historian Dr. Matthew Algeo. "It cursed like a sailor. It disrupted the funeral. The mourners were horrified." The story comes from the Reverend William Menefee Norment, who claimed to have witnessed the incident. According to Norment, the parrot "let loose a volley of oaths" that "fairly made the women blush." "The parrot had to be removed," said Algeo. "It was causing a scene. The funeral was a solemn occasion. The parrot didn't care." The story has never been definitively proven. Some historians doubt it happened. Others believe it is true. "It's plausible," said Algeo. "Jackson loved his parrot. He taught it to curse. The parrot loved him back. It made sense that it would mourn him in its own way." Whether true or not, the story of Andrew Jackson's swearing parrot has become part of American folklore. "It's a good story," said Algeo. "It captures something about Jackson. He was a rough man. He was a fighter. He cursed. His parrot cursed. It's fitting."`,
