    image: "https://i.natgeofe.com/n/97fd0a3f-7ca1-4686-81ff-e3d4d1f4bb79/DP135504_16x9.jpg?w=1200",
    content: `When we think of samurai, we think of men. But Japan had female samurai. They were called "onna-bugeisha." They fought alongside men. They led armies. They died in battle. Their stories have been largely forgotten. "The onna-bugeisha were warriors," said historian Dr. Katsuya Hirano. "They trained in martial arts. They carried weapons. They fought to protect their families and their honor." The most famous onna-bugeisha was Tomoe Gozen, who lived in the 12th century. She fought in the Genpei War, leading 300 samurai against 2,000 enemies. She decapitated the enemy leader. "Tomoe was a legend," said Hirano. "She was beautiful, intelligent, and deadly. She was respected by both her allies and her enemies." Another notable onna-bugeisha was Nakano Takeko, who fought in the Boshin War in 1868. She led a unit of female warriors against the imperial army. She was killed in battle, dying with her sword in her hand. "Nakano was a hero," said Hirano. "She fought for what she believed in. She died for what she believed in. She is remembered as a symbol of loyalty and courage." The onna-bugeisha used a weapon called the "naginata," a polearm with a curved blade. The naginata was effective at keeping enemies at a distance, allowing the female samurai to use their agility and speed to their advantage. "The naginata was the weapon of choice for female samurai," said Hirano. "It was versatile. It was deadly. It allowed them to fight on equal terms with men." The role of women in samurai society was complex. They were expected to be loyal, obedient, and self-sacrificing. But they were also expected to be warriors. "The samurai code, bushido, applied to women as well as men," said Hirano. "Women were expected to defend their homes and their honor. They were trained to fight." The onna-bugeisha have been largely erased from popular history. "The stories were suppressed," said Hirano. "The Meiji government wanted to present a modern, Westernized image of Japan. Female warriors did not fit that image. Their stories were forgotten." Today, the onna-bugeisha are being rediscovered. "It's time to remember them," said Hirano. "They were warriors. They were heroes. They deserve to be honored."`,
    featured: true
