    content: `Subutai was a general of the Mongol Empire. He served under Genghis Khan and his successor, Ögedei Khan. He conquered more territory than any general in history. He never lost a battle. And most people have never heard of him. "Subutai was a genius," said historian Dr. Timothy May. "He was a master of strategy, logistics, and psychology. He defeated armies that outnumbered his own. He conquered nations that were thought unconquerable. He was the greatest general of his age." Subutai was born a commoner. He rose through the ranks because of his skill. He was illiterate, but he had a photographic memory. He could recall terrain, troop movements, and supply routes with perfect accuracy. "He never forgot anything," said May. "He could look at a map once and remember every detail. It was an extraordinary gift." Subutai's greatest campaign was the invasion of Europe in 1241. He led an army of 50,000 Mongol horsemen against a coalition of European knights. The Mongols defeated the Poles at the Battle of Legnica and the Hungarians at the Battle of Mohi. "The Mongols were unstoppable," said May. "They used feigned retreats, encirclements, and psychological warfare. The Europeans had never seen anything like it." Subutai was planning to invade Germany when news arrived of Ögedei Khan's death. The Mongol princes returned to Mongolia to elect a new leader. Europe was saved. "If Ögedei had lived, Subutai would have conquered Europe," said May. "There was no army that could have stopped him. It's one of the great 'what ifs' of history." Subutai retired in 1248. He died at the age of 72, having never lost a battle. "He was undefeated," said May. "No other general can claim that. Not Alexander. Not Caesar. Not Napoleon. Only Subutai."`,
