    content: `The Three Kingdoms Period (220-280 AD) was a century of chaos, war, and intrigue in China. The Han dynasty had collapsed. Three rival kingdoms — Wei, Shu, and Wu — fought for control of the empire. The period has been romanticized in literature, film, and video games. "The Three Kingdoms is China's 'Game of Thrones,'" said historian Dr. Rafe de Crespigny. "It has everything: epic battles, cunning strategies, heroic warriors, tragic betrayals. It's the story of how China was forged." The most famous work about the period is "Romance of the Three Kingdoms," a 14th-century novel by Luo Guanzhong. The novel is a fictionalized account of the period, blending history with legend. "The novel is a masterpiece," said de Crespigny. "It's one of the four great classical novels of Chinese literature. It has shaped how the Chinese understand their history." The heroes of the Three Kingdoms are still celebrated today. Guan Yu, a general of Shu, is worshiped as a god of war. Zhuge Liang, a strategist of Shu, is considered the wisest man in Chinese history. "These figures are larger than life," said de Crespigny. "They have become symbols of loyalty, wisdom, and courage. They are part of the Chinese identity." The Three Kingdoms Period ended in 280 AD, when the Jin dynasty unified China. But the legacy of the period lives on. "It was a time of suffering," said de Crespigny. "Millions died. The land was devastated. But out of that suffering came stories that have inspired generations. It's a reminder that even in the darkest times, there is hope."`,
