    content: `On November 5, 1605, a group of Catholic conspirators led by Robert Catesby attempted to blow up the British Parliament. They placed 36 barrels of gunpowder in a cellar beneath the House of Lords. They planned to kill King James I and the entire Protestant government. "The Gunpowder Plot was a terrorist attack," said historian Dr. Antonia Fraser. "It was a desperate act by a desperate minority. It failed. But it changed history." The plot was foiled when an anonymous letter warned a Catholic lord to stay away from Parliament. The authorities searched the cellars and found Guy Fawkes guarding the gunpowder. "Fawkes was tortured until he confessed," said Fraser. "He gave up the names of his co-conspirators. They were all killed or executed." The Gunpowder Plot led to harsh reprisals against Catholics. They were barred from public office. They were forbidden to own weapons. They were subjected to fines and imprisonment. "It was a crackdown," said Fraser. "The government was terrified. They wanted to make sure no one tried anything like that again." The plot is still commemorated every year on November 5. Britons burn effigies of Guy Fawkes on bonfires. They set off fireworks. They sing: "Remember, remember, the fifth of November, gunpowder, treason and plot." "It's a strange tradition," said Fraser. "We celebrate the failure of a terrorist attack. It's a reminder that history is complicated."`,
