    content: `In 1947, the House Un-American Activities Committee began investigating communist influence in Hollywood. Witnesses were called to testify. They were asked to name names. Those who refused were blacklisted. "The Hollywood blacklist destroyed lives," said historian Dr. Thomas Doherty. "Hundreds of writers, directors, and actors lost their jobs. They were unable to work in their profession. Some went to prison. Some committed suicide." The most famous victims were the Hollywood Ten. They refused to testify before the committee. They were cited for contempt of Congress and sent to prison. "They took a stand," said Doherty. "They said that the committee had no right to ask about their political beliefs. They paid the price." The blacklist lasted for more than a decade. It was eventually broken by directors like Otto Preminger and Kirk Douglas, who hired blacklisted writers under pseudonyms. "The blacklist was a dark chapter in American history," said Doherty. "It showed how fear can lead to injustice. It's a lesson we should not forget."`,
