    content: `The Edo period (1603-1868) was a time of peace, prosperity, and isolation in Japan. The Tokugawa shogunate ruled with an iron fist. The country was closed to foreigners. The samurai class was at the top of a rigid social hierarchy. "Edo was a paradox," said historian Dr. Marius Jansen. "It was a time of peace, but the samurai were still warriors. It was a time of prosperity, but the peasants were still poor. It was a time of cultural flowering, but political dissent was crushed." The Edo period saw the rise of a vibrant urban culture. Kabuki theater, woodblock prints, and haiku poetry flourished. The "floating world" of pleasure districts offered escape from the rigid social order. "It was a golden age of art," said Jansen. "The woodblock prints of Hokusai and Hiroshige are masterpieces. They are still celebrated today." But the Edo period was also a time of repression. Christians were persecuted. Foreigners were expelled. The government monitored the population through a system of neighborhood registers. "The shogunate was a police state," said Jansen. "They controlled everything. They tolerated no dissent." The Edo period ended in 1868 with the Meiji Restoration. Japan opened to the world. The samurai class was abolished. The country embarked on a path of rapid modernization. "The Edo period is remembered with nostalgia," said Jansen. "It was a time of peace. It was a time of art. But it was also a time of oppression. It's a complicated legacy."`,
