    content: `The Thirty Years' War (1618-1648) was one of the most destructive conflicts in European history. It began as a religious war between Protestants and Catholics. It evolved into a struggle for political power. By the time it ended, 8 million people were dead. "Germany was devastated," said historian Dr. Peter Wilson. "One-third of the population died. Entire regions were depopulated. The economy was destroyed. It took generations to recover." The war was fought by mercenary armies. They lived off the land. They looted, burned, and raped. They spread disease. "The soldiers were not paid," said Wilson. "They were expected to support themselves. That meant plunder. The civilian population suffered terribly." The war ended with the Peace of Westphalia in 1648. The treaty established the principle of state sovereignty. It recognized the right of each German state to choose its own religion. "Westphalia is considered the beginning of the modern international system," said Wilson. "It ended the idea of a single Christian commonwealth. It recognized that states had the right to govern themselves." The Thirty Years' War is a cautionary tale. "It shows what happens when religion and politics mix," said Wilson. "It shows the horrors of war. It shows the importance of peace."`,
