    content: `On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy learned that the Soviet Union was installing nuclear missiles in Cuba. The missiles could reach Washington in minutes. The world was on the brink of nuclear war. "The Cuban Missile Crisis was the closest we have ever come to annihilation," said historian Dr. Michael Dobbs. "For 13 days, the world held its breath. One wrong move could have ended civilization." Kennedy imposed a naval blockade around Cuba. Soviet ships approached. The world waited. "It was a game of chicken," said Dobbs. "Both sides were bluffing. But if the bluff failed, millions would die." The crisis was resolved when Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev agreed to remove the missiles in exchange for a US promise not to invade Cuba. The US also secretly agreed to remove missiles from Turkey. "It was a compromise," said Dobbs. "Neither side won. But neither side lost. The world survived." The Cuban Missile Crisis is a reminder of the dangers of nuclear weapons. "We came close to disaster," said Dobbs. "We have never come that close again. But the threat remains."`,
