    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://physicsworld.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Perkowitz_Payne-Gaposchkin.jpeg",
    content: `In 1925, a 25-year-old British astronomer named Cecilia Payne submitted her doctoral thesis at Harvard. In it, she made a revolutionary claim: stars are made primarily of hydrogen and helium, not heavy elements like iron and silicon as previously believed. The scientific establishment dismissed her. "Payne's conclusion was correct," said astronomer Dr. Jocelyn Bell Burnell. "But the leading astronomers of the day, including Henry Norris Russell, told her it was impossible. They said she must have made a mistake." Payne was devastated. She added a note to her thesis saying the results were "almost certainly not real." But she was right. Russell himself proved her correct four years later — without giving her credit. "Russell essentially rediscovered what Payne had already discovered," said Bell Burnell. "He eventually acknowledged her work, but the damage was done. She never got the recognition she deserved." Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin (she added her husband's name later) spent her career at Harvard. She became the first woman to be promoted to full professor at the university. She was the first woman to chair a department. "She was a pioneer," said Bell Burnell. "She opened doors for women in astronomy. But her greatest discovery — what stars are made of — is still not as widely known as it should be." Payne's story is a reminder of the barriers women in science have faced. "She was brilliant," said Bell Burnell. "She was right. And she was ignored because she was a woman. That is a tragedy."`,
