    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://images.newscientist.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/05144245/alice_ball2ebcm37.jpg",
    content: `Alice Augusta Ball was a young chemist at the University of Hawaii. In 1915, she developed a treatment for leprosy that was more effective than anything before it. She was 24 years old. She died soon after, before she could publish her results. "Ball's work was revolutionary," said historian Dr. Dawn Collins. "Leprosy was a terrifying disease. Patients were isolated in colonies. They had no hope. Ball gave them hope." Ball's treatment, known as the "Ball Method," involved injecting chaulmoogra oil, a traditional remedy, in a form that could be absorbed by the body. It was the first effective treatment for leprosy. "She solved a problem that had stumped scientists for decades," said Collins. "She was brilliant. And she did it as a young woman of color in a field dominated by white men." After Ball's death, a man named Arthur Dean took credit for her work. He published her results under his own name. The treatment became known as the "Dean Method." "He stole her work," said Collins. "For decades, no one knew that Ball was the real inventor. It was a travesty." In 2000, the University of Hawaii finally recognized Ball's contribution. They established a day in her honor. They placed a plaque on the only chaulmoogra tree on campus. "It was a long-overdue recognition," said Collins. "Alice Ball deserved better. She should be remembered as a pioneer."`,
