    image: "https://whyy.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/file-20190205-86205-ff9763.jpg",
    content: `Lise Meitner was an Austrian physicist who, along with Otto Hahn, discovered nuclear fission. But when it came time for the Nobel Prize, only Hahn was recognized. Meitner was ignored. "It was a scandal," said physicist Dr. Ruth Lewin Sime. "Meitner was the intellectual leader of the team. She understood what was happening. Hahn didn't. But she was Jewish. She had fled the Nazis. She was a woman. The Nobel committee chose Hahn." Meitner and Hahn worked together for 30 years. They were close friends. But after the Nazis annexed Austria in 1938, Meitner was forced to flee. She escaped to Sweden. "She left everything behind," said Sime. "Her home. Her colleagues. Her research. She had to start over." In Sweden, Meitner continued her work. She and her nephew, Otto Frisch, were the first to explain the process of nuclear fission. They coined the term. "They realized that the uranium atom had split," said Sime. "They calculated the energy released. They understood that this could be used to build an atomic bomb." When Hahn published the results, he downplayed Meitner's role. He was rewarded with the Nobel Prize in 1944. "Meitner was nominated 49 times," said Sime. "She never won. It's one of the biggest injustices in the history of science." Meitner was offered a position on the Manhattan Project. She refused. "I will have nothing to do with a bomb," she said. "I want to create, not destroy." Meitner died in 1968. In her later years, she was finally recognized for her contributions. An element, meitnerium, was named after her. "It was a small consolation," said Sime. "She deserved more. She deserved the Nobel."`,
