    image: "https://media.labcompare.com/m/53/article/596544.jpg",
    content: `In 1952, Rosalind Franklin captured Photo 51 — an X-ray diffraction image of DNA that revealed its double helix structure. The image was shown to James Watson and Francis Crick without her permission. They used it to build their famous model. "Franklin's work was essential," said biologist Dr. Matthew Cobb. "Without Photo 51, Watson and Crick would not have discovered the double helix. They admitted as much." Franklin was not credited in their initial paper. She was not nominated for the Nobel Prize when it was awarded to Watson, Crick, and Maurice Wilkins in 1962. By then, she had died of cancer at the age of 37. "She was cheated," said Cobb. "Her work was stolen. She never got the recognition she deserved." Franklin was a brilliant scientist. She was meticulous. She was exacting. She was also difficult to work with — at least according to her male colleagues. "The men didn't like her," said Cobb. "She didn't fit their idea of what a woman should be. They dismissed her. They marginalized her. They stole her work." In recent years, Franklin's contributions have been recognized. Books have been written. Documentaries have been made. A building at King's College London is named after her. "It's too little, too late," said Cobb. "But it's something. We can't change the past. But we can honor her memory."`,
