    image: "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/z_3zNw91MSY/maxresdefault.jpg",
    content: `In 1967, a graduate student named Jocelyn Bell noticed a strange signal in her data. It was a series of regular pulses. She initially thought it was interference. Then she realized it was something new: a pulsar. "It was one of the greatest discoveries of the 20th century," said astrophysicist Dr. Neil deGrasse Tyson. "Bell Burnell discovered a new type of star. She was 24 years old." The 1974 Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded for the discovery of pulsars. The recipients were Bell Burnell's supervisor, Antony Hewish, and another astronomer, Martin Ryle. Bell Burnell was not included. "It was a travesty," said Tyson. "She did the work. She made the discovery. She was left out because she was a student — and because she was a woman." Bell Burnell handled the snub with grace. "I am not bitter," she has said. "I understand how the system works. But I do think it was unfair." In 2018, Bell Burnell was awarded a $3 million Breakthrough Prize for her discovery. She donated the money to fund scholarships for women and underrepresented minorities in physics. "That's who she is," said Tyson. "She turned injustice into opportunity. She is a hero."`,
