    content: `In the 1840s, Ignaz Semmelweis was a doctor at a Vienna hospital. He noticed that women in one maternity ward were dying at a much higher rate than women in another. The only difference: the high-mortality ward was staffed by doctors who also performed autopsies. "Semmelweis made the connection," said historian Dr. Sherwin Nuland. "He realized that doctors were carrying something from the dead to the living. He ordered them to wash their hands." Handwashing reduced mortality from 18 percent to 2 percent. It was a miracle. But Semmelweis's colleagues rejected his findings. "They were offended," said Nuland. "They didn't want to admit that they had been killing their patients. They mocked him. They dismissed him." Semmelweis grew frustrated. He wrote angry letters. He called his colleagues murderers. He alienated his allies. Eventually, he was committed to an insane asylum. "He died there, probably beaten to death by guards," said Nuland. "He was only 47. He died believing that he had failed." Years after Semmelweis's death, Louis Pasteur's germ theory of disease vindicated him. Handwashing became standard practice. But the damage was done. "Semmelweis was right," said Nuland. "He was a hero. He was treated like a fool. His story is a tragedy."`,
