    content: `Satyendra Nath Bose was an Indian physicist. In 1924, he derived a new way to understand Planck's law of blackbody radiation. He submitted his paper to a journal. It was rejected. "The reviewers didn't understand it," said physicist Dr. Manan Sharma. "They told Bose his derivation was flawed. They were wrong." Bose sent his paper to Albert Einstein. Einstein recognized its importance immediately. He translated it into German and submitted it to a journal himself. "Einstein said Bose had made a significant discovery," said Sharma. "He extended Bose's work to create a new type of quantum statistics." The result was Bose-Einstein statistics and the concept of bosons — particles that can occupy the same quantum state. The Higgs boson, discovered in 2012, is named in honor of Bose. "Bose's work is foundational to modern physics," said Sharma. "But he never won the Nobel Prize. He was overlooked. It's a shame." Bose spent his career in India, training a generation of physicists. He was a brilliant teacher and a generous mentor. "He didn't care about fame," said Sharma. "He cared about science. He cared about his students. He was a true guru."`,
