    content: `Alfred Russel Wallace was a naturalist who spent years in the Amazon and the Malay Archipelago. In 1858, he developed a theory of evolution by natural selection — independently of Charles Darwin. He wrote to Darwin, who was shocked. "Darwin had been working on the same theory for 20 years," said historian Dr. John van Wyhe. "He had not published because he was afraid of the backlash. Wallace's letter forced his hand." The Linnean Society published papers by both Darwin and Wallace in 1858. But Darwin's "On the Origin of Species," published in 1859, overshadowed Wallace's work. "Darwin got the fame," said van Wyhe. "Wallace got the footnote. It's not entirely fair." Wallace was a socialist. He believed in spiritualism. He was not a member of the scientific establishment. "He was an outsider," said van Wyhe. "Darwin was an insider. That mattered." Despite his marginalization, Wallace continued to work. He wrote books. He discovered the Wallace Line, which separates Asian and Australian fauna. "He was a brilliant scientist," said van Wyhe. "He deserves to be remembered as more than just Darwin's rival."`,
