    content: `Emmy Noether was a mathematician. She was brilliant. She was also a woman. In early 20th-century Germany, that was a problem. "Noether was not allowed to teach at the University of Göttingen," said physicist Dr. Helen Quinn. "She lectured under other professors' names. She was paid nothing." Despite the discrimination, Noether produced groundbreaking work. Her most famous contribution is Noether's theorem, which links symmetries to conservation laws. "Noether's theorem explains why energy is conserved," said Quinn. "It explains why momentum is conserved. It is one of the most elegant and important results in theoretical physics." Albert Einstein called Noether a "creative mathematical genius." But she never got the recognition she deserved. "She was nominated for the Nobel Prize multiple times," said Quinn. "She never won. She died in 1935, largely unknown." Noether's story is a reminder of the barriers women have faced. "She was one of the greatest mathematicians of her generation," said Quinn. "She was treated as a second-class citizen. It's a tragedy."`,
