    content: `Vera Rubin was fascinated by stars from a young age. She wanted to be an astronomer. Her father encouraged her. But her teachers told her it was not a suitable profession for a woman. "Rubin ignored them," said astronomer Dr. Emily Levesque. "She pursued her passion. She earned a PhD. She faced discrimination at every step." Rubin's most important work involved measuring the rotation speeds of galaxies. She found that stars at the edges of galaxies were moving as fast as stars near the center. "That shouldn't happen," said Levesque. "The laws of gravity say that stars at the edge should move more slowly. Rubin's observation meant that there was more mass in the galaxies than we could see. She had discovered evidence for dark matter." Rubin's findings were initially dismissed. "Astronomers didn't believe her," said Levesque. "They said she must have made a mistake. She hadn't." Over time, Rubin's evidence accumulated. Other astronomers confirmed her results. Dark matter is now accepted as a major component of the universe. "Rubin should have won the Nobel Prize," said Levesque. "She was nominated many times. She never won. It's a scandal." Rubin died in 2016. A telescope and a ridge on Mars are named after her. "It's not enough," said Levesque. "But it's something. She will not be forgotten."`,
