    image: "https://alumniandfriends.uchicago.edu/servlet/rtaImage?eid=a4X8Z000000E0XK&feoid=00N1U00000TnrKR&refid=0EM8Z000005iNgV",
    content: `In 1930, a young Indian physicist named Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar was on a ship to England. He had discovered something extraordinary: there was a maximum mass for a white dwarf star. Above that limit, the star would collapse into something new — something we now call a black hole. "Chandrasekhar was 19 years old," said astrophysicist Dr. Priyamvada Natarajan. "He had solved a problem that had stumped the greatest minds. His discovery was revolutionary." But when Chandrasekhar presented his findings, he was ridiculed. The famous astrophysicist Arthur Eddington publicly dismissed him. "Eddington said Chandrasekhar's idea was absurd," said Natarajan. "He called it 'stellar buffoonery.' It was a brutal attack." Chandrasekhar was devastated. He considered giving up. But he persisted. He continued his research. He moved to the United States. He built a career. "He was one of the great astrophysicists of the 20th century," said Natarajan. "He won the Nobel Prize in 1983. Eddington was proved wrong." The limit Chandrasekhar discovered — the Chandrasekhar limit — is now fundamental to our understanding of stars and black holes. "He was right," said Natarajan. "He knew he was right. But he had to wait 50 years for the world to admit it."`,
