    image: "https://www.amightygirl.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/mary-anning-blog-web.jpg",
    content: `Mary Anning was born in 1799 in Lyme Regis, England. Her family was poor. She had no formal education. She spent her childhood searching the cliffs for fossils to sell to tourists. "Anning was a naturalist," said historian Dr. Patricia Fara. "She had an eye for fossils. She found things that scientists had never seen." In 1811, Anning discovered the first complete ichthyosaur skeleton. She was 12 years old. Later, she found the first complete plesiosaur and the first pterodactyl outside Germany. "Her discoveries changed paleontology," said Fara. "But she was not allowed to join the scientific societies. She was a woman. She was poor. The men took credit for her work." Anning struggled financially her entire life. She died in 1847 of breast cancer. "She was never given the recognition she deserved," said Fara. "It's only in recent years that her story has been told." The rhyme "She sells seashells by the seashore" is about Mary Anning. "It's a small tribute," said Fara. "But she deserves more. She deserves to be remembered as one of the greatest fossil hunters in history."`,
