    image: "https://media-cldnry.s-nbcnews.com/image/upload/t_social_share_1024x768_scale,f_auto,q_auto:best/rockcms/2021-02/210211-chien-shiung-wu-jm-1028-c428ea.jpg",
    content: `Chien-Shiung Wu was a Chinese-American physicist. In 1956, she designed an experiment to test whether parity was conserved in weak nuclear interactions. The experiment was difficult. It required extreme cold, careful measurement, and months of work. "Wu did the hard work," said physicist Dr. Nina Byers. "She was the one who made the experiment work. She was the one who got the results." The results were shocking: parity was violated. A fundamental law of physics was wrong. "Wu had overturned a century of thinking," said Byers. "It was one of the most important experiments in the history of physics." The Nobel Prize for the discovery was awarded to the theorists who proposed the experiment, Tsung-Dao Lee and Chen-Ning Yang. Wu was not included. "It was an outrage," said Byers. "She did the work. She got the results. She should have been on the podium." Wu never won the Nobel. She continued to work, earning numerous other honors. She was the first woman to serve as president of the American Physical Society. "She was a pioneer," said Byers. "She opened doors for women in physics. She was not bitter about the Nobel. But she should have won."`,
