    image: "https://storage.googleapis.com/wp-static/wp_globalehsan_pillar/2023/11/0ed42408-ibn-sina-avicenna.jpg",
    content: `Ibn Sina, known in the West as Avicenna, was one of the greatest minds of the Islamic Golden Age. Born in 980 in what is now Uzbekistan, he was a child prodigy. By age 16, he had mastered medicine. By age 18, he had treated a king. "Ibn Sina was a polymath," said historian Dr. George Saliba. "He wrote on medicine, philosophy, astronomy, chemistry, geology, and poetry. He was one of the most influential thinkers of the Middle Ages." Ibn Sina's most famous work is "The Canon of Medicine," a five-volume encyclopedia that synthesized the medical knowledge of the time. It was translated into Latin and became the standard medical text in Europe for 500 years. "The Canon was used in universities until the 17th century," said Saliba. "It was more influential than any other medical book. It saved countless lives." Ibn Sina also made important contributions to philosophy. His synthesis of Aristotle and Islamic theology influenced Thomas Aquinas and other medieval thinkers. "He was a giant," said Saliba. "His ideas shaped both the Islamic world and the West." Ibn Sina died in 1037 at the age of 56. His legacy lives on. "He is still studied today," said Saliba. "His ideas are still debated. That is the mark of a true genius."`,
