    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/GGl6d8LXEAA_tJP.jpg",
    content: `Oliver Heaviside was a self-taught English mathematician. He was eccentric. He rarely left his home. He communicated with the outside world via postcards. But he was also a genius. "Heaviside transformed electromagnetism," said physicist Dr. John Gribbin. "He took James Clerk Maxwell's original 20 equations and simplified them into the four vector equations we use today. That alone would have been enough for a legacy." Heaviside also predicted the existence of the ionosphere, a layer of charged particles in the upper atmosphere that reflects radio waves. "He was ridiculed at the time," said Gribbin. "But he was right. The ionosphere is named after him." Heaviside invented operational calculus, a mathematical technique that is still used in engineering. He coined the terms "impedance," "inductance," and "conductance." "He was a pioneer," said Gribbin. "He made it possible to understand and use electricity." Heaviside died in 1925, largely forgotten. "He was a difficult man," said Gribbin. "He alienated his colleagues. He fought with the establishment. But he was brilliant. He deserves to be remembered."`,
