    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://www.montana.edu/mbi/images/Hilleman2.jpg",
    content: `Maurice Hilleman is the most successful vaccinologist in history. He developed more than 40 vaccines, including those for measles, mumps, rubella, hepatitis A and B, and meningitis. "Hilleman saved more lives than any other scientist of the 20th century," said Dr. Paul Offit, author of "Vaccinated." "His vaccines prevent millions of deaths every year. He is a hero." Hilleman's work was not always appreciated. He was a perfectionist. He was demanding. He pushed his colleagues hard. "He was difficult," said Offit. "But he was right. His vaccines worked." In 1963, Hilleman's daughter developed mumps. He isolated the virus from her throat and turned it into a vaccine. The vaccine was licensed in 1967. "He didn't wait," said Offit. "He acted. He saved countless children from a painful disease." Hilleman died in 2005. His name is not widely known. "That's a tragedy," said Offit. "He should be a household name. He did more for human health than almost anyone."`,
