    excerpt: "She was the greatest female scholar of antiquity. She was killed by a Christian mob for her ideas.",
    category: "History",
    author: "Mehedi Redoy",
    date: "April 22, 2026",
    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://mlcsea8zxbt5.i.optimole.com/cb:nyUo.2f207/w:1024/h:923/q:mauto/f:best/ig:avif/https://www.womensvoicesnow.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Hypatia-of-Alexandria-The-Philosopher-Who-Defied-Darkness-with-Knowledge.jpg",
    content: `Hypatia of Alexandria was a mathematician, astronomer, and philosopher. She lived in the late 4th and early 5th centuries AD. She was the daughter of Theon, a famous mathematician. She was smarter than her father. "Hypatia was the greatest female scholar of antiquity," said historian Dr. Maria Dzielska. "She was respected by pagans and Christians alike. She taught students from across the Roman Empire." Hypatia wrote commentaries on geometry, algebra, and astronomy. She invented the astrolabe and the hydrometer. She was a beloved teacher. "She was also a symbol," said Dzielska. "She represented reason, learning, and the classical tradition. That made her a target." In 415 AD, a Christian mob attacked Hypatia. They dragged her from her chariot, stripped her, and killed her with roof tiles. Her body was burned. "Her murder was a turning point," said Dzielska. "It marked the end of classical Alexandria. It signaled the rise of religious intolerance." Hypatia has become a symbol of intellectual freedom. Her story has been told in books, films, and art. "She died for knowledge," said Dzielska. "She should be remembered as a martyr for reason."`,
