    category: "History",
    author: "Mehedi Redoy",
    date: "April 22, 2026",
    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://www.nobelprize.org/images/tu-13648-landscape-medium.jpg",
    content: `Tu Youyou was a Chinese scientist working on a secret military project during the Vietnam War. The project's goal: find a cure for malaria. The Viet Cong were suffering from drug-resistant malaria. China wanted to help. "Tu was not a pharmacologist," said historian Dr. Zhang Lijia. "She was a medical researcher. She had no experience with drug discovery. But she was put in charge of the project." Tu turned to traditional Chinese medicine. She scoured ancient texts. She found a reference to sweet wormwood, which had been used to treat fevers for 1,000 years. "She extracted the active ingredient, artemisinin," said Zhang. "It was a breakthrough. Artemisinin was more effective than any existing malaria drug." Tu's discovery saved millions of lives. Malaria deaths fell by 60 percent. "She never patented her discovery," said Zhang. "She wanted it to be available to everyone. She was not interested in money." In 2015, Tu Youyou won the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine. She was 85 years old. "It was a long-overdue recognition," said Zhang. "She had been working in obscurity for decades. She deserved the honor."`,
