    content: `Hedy Lamarr was a Hollywood star in the 1930s and 40s. She was called "the most beautiful woman in the world." But she was also a brilliant inventor. "Lamarr had a curious mind," said historian Dr. Richard Rhodes. "She invented things. She solved problems. She was a natural engineer." During World War II, Lamarr and composer George Antheil invented a frequency-hopping system for guiding torpedoes. The idea was to prevent the enemy from jamming the signal. "The technology was years ahead of its time," said Rhodes. "The Navy was not interested. They said a movie star could not be a serious inventor." Lamarr's patent expired in 1959. Years later, the technology was rediscovered and used in Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, and GPS. "She finally received recognition in her old age," said Rhodes. "She was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame. She died in 2000, knowing that her work had changed the world."`,
