    content: `Muhammad ibn Musa al-Khwarizmi was a Persian scholar who lived in the 9th century. He worked at the House of Wisdom in Baghdad, the intellectual center of the Islamic Golden Age. "Al-Khwarizmi wrote the first systematic textbook on algebra," said historian Dr. George Saliba. "The word 'algebra' comes from the title of his book, 'Al-Jabr.' His name gave us 'algorithm.'" Al-Khwarizmi also introduced Indian numerals to the Islamic world. The numerals we use today — 1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,0 — are sometimes called "Arabic numerals" because of his influence. "He was a giant," said Saliba. "His work shaped mathematics for centuries." Al-Khwarizmi's books were translated into Latin in the 12th century. They became standard textbooks in European universities. "He was one of the most influential scholars in history," said Saliba. "But many people have never heard of him."`,
