    content: `In 1856, Eunice Foote conducted a simple experiment. She placed glass cylinders filled with different gases in the sun. She measured how hot they got. She found that the cylinder with carbon dioxide became the hottest. "Foote had discovered the greenhouse effect," said historian Dr. Kathleen Friery. "She had shown that CO2 traps heat. It was a revolutionary insight." Foote's paper was presented at a scientific conference in 1856. But she was not allowed to present it herself. A male scientist read it for her. "Three years later, John Tyndall published a similar experiment," said Friery. "He is often credited with discovering the greenhouse effect. Foote is forgotten." Foote's work has been rediscovered in recent years. She is now recognized as a pioneer of climate science. "She was ahead of her time," said Friery. "She should be remembered."`,
