    content: `Barbara McClintock was a geneticist. She studied corn. In the 1940s, she discovered that genes can move from one location to another on a chromosome. She called them "jumping genes." "The idea was radical," said biologist Dr. Evelyn Fox Keller. "The scientific establishment did not believe her. They said her data was flawed. They said she was wrong." McClintock was ostracized. She stopped publishing. She stopped presenting. She worked in isolation. "She was ahead of her time," said Keller. "It took decades for the rest of science to catch up." In the 1960s and 70s, other scientists discovered transposons — jumping genes — in bacteria and other organisms. McClintock was vindicated. "She was proved right," said Keller. "In 1983, she won the Nobel Prize. She was 81 years old." McClintock's story is a reminder that science is not always open to new ideas. "It can be cruel," said Keller. "But the truth eventually wins."`,
