    image: "https://www.magiscenter.com/hubfs/Imported_Blog_Media/Georges-Lemaitre-Father-Big-Bang-Theory-Magis-Center.jpg",
    content: `Georges Lemaître was a Belgian priest and astronomer. In 1927, he proposed that the universe began as a single point — a "Primeval Atom" — and has been expanding ever since. "It was the Big Bang theory," said astrophysicist Dr. Owen Gingerich. "Lemaître had solved the problem of cosmic origins. He was right." But when Lemaître met Albert Einstein in 1927, Einstein dismissed his idea. "Your physics is abominable," Einstein said. Lemaître was crushed. "He did not give up," said Gingerich. "He continued his work. He published his theory. It was largely ignored." In 1929, Edwin Hubble discovered that the universe is expanding. Lemaître's theory was suddenly relevant. Einstein visited Lemaître and apologized. "He said, 'This is the most beautiful and satisfactory explanation of creation to which I have ever listened,'" said Gingerich. "It was a full mea culpa." Lemaître was a devout Catholic. He saw no conflict between his faith and his science. "He believed that God created the universe," said Gingerich. "He was comfortable with that mystery."`,
