    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://investigatingpower.nyc3.digitaloceanspaces.com/2017/07/headshot-carson-800x450.jpg",
    content: `Rachel Carson was a marine biologist and writer. In 1962, she published "Silent Spring," a book about the dangers of pesticides. It changed the world. "Carson's book was a bombshell," said historian Dr. Linda Lear. "She showed that DDT and other pesticides were killing birds, poisoning the environment, and threatening human health. It was a wake-up call." The chemical industry attacked Carson. They called her a hysterical woman. They said her science was flawed. They tried to discredit her. "She was dying of cancer," said Lear. "She was in pain. But she fought back. She testified before Congress. She defended her work." Carson's book led to the ban of DDT in the United States. It inspired the creation of the Environmental Protection Agency. It launched the modern environmental movement. "She was a hero," said Lear. "She stood up to powerful interests. She spoke for the voiceless — for the birds, for the fish, for the planet." Carson died in 1964. She did not live to see the full impact of her work. "But she knew," said Lear. "She knew that she had made a difference."`,
