    content: `Nikola Tesla was a Serbian-American inventor. He invented the alternating current (AC) electrical system that powers the modern world. He also invented the Tesla coil, radio remote control, and the induction motor. "Tesla was a visionary," said historian Dr. Marc Seifer. "He saw the future. He dreamed of wireless power, of global communication, of a world run by electricity. Many of his ideas have come true." Tesla worked for Thomas Edison early in his career. They feuded over AC versus DC electricity. Edison favored DC. Tesla favored AC. AC won. "Edison was a great inventor," said Seifer. "But he was also a ruthless businessman. He tried to discredit Tesla. He failed." Despite his genius, Tesla was never good with money. He sold his patents for pennies. He died in 1943, alone and in debt. "He was a tragic figure," said Seifer. "He was brilliant, but he was also eccentric. He alienated his allies. He was forgotten for decades." Today, Tesla is celebrated as a hero. His name adorns electric cars, tech companies, and museums. "He finally got the recognition he deserved," said Seifer. "Better late than never."`,
