    content: `Marie Curie is one of the most famous scientists in history. She discovered radium and polonium. She won two Nobel Prizes — one in physics, one in chemistry. She was the first woman to win a Nobel. She remains the only person to win Nobels in two different sciences. "Curie was a genius," said physicist Dr. Nina Byers. "She also faced enormous discrimination. She was a woman. She was Polish. She was an outsider." Curie did her early work in a leaky shed. She processed tons of pitchblende to extract a tiny amount of radium. "The conditions were terrible," said Byers. "But she persevered. She discovered something new." Despite her achievements, Curie was denied membership in the French Academy of Sciences. The Academy had never admitted a woman. It would not admit her. "It was a humiliation," said Byers. "She was the greatest scientist in France. They rejected her because of her gender." Curie died in 1934 of aplastic anemia, caused by exposure to radiation. Her notebooks are still radioactive. They are kept in a lead-lined box. "She gave her life for science," said Byers. "She deserves to be remembered."`,
