    image: "https://www.jic.ac.uk/app/uploads/2019/01/Fig-1_mendel-e1547030537843.jpg",
    content: `Gregor Mendel was a monk in what is now the Czech Republic. In the 1850s and 60s, he conducted experiments on pea plants. He crossed plants with different traits — tall vs. short, green vs. yellow, smooth vs. wrinkled. He counted the results. "Mendel discovered the laws of inheritance," said biologist Dr. Michael Dunn. "He showed that traits are passed from parents to offspring in predictable patterns. He founded the science of genetics." Mendel published his results in 1866. The scientific community ignored them. "His work was too ahead of its time," said Dunn. "No one understood what he had found. His paper was cited only a handful of times." Mendel died in 1884, still unknown. In 1900, three other scientists independently rediscovered his laws. "They were stunned," said Dunn. "Mendel had solved the problem decades earlier. He had been forgotten." Mendel is now celebrated as the father of genetics. His laws are taught in every biology class. "He was a modest man," said Dunn. "He never knew how important his work would become."`,
