    content: `Dmitri Mendeleev was a Russian chemist. In 1869, he created the periodic table of elements. He arranged the 63 known elements by atomic weight and chemical properties. "Mendeleev saw patterns that others had missed," said chemist Dr. Eric Scerri. "He realized that the properties of elements repeat periodically. His table was a work of genius." Mendeleev left gaps in his table. He predicted that new elements would be discovered to fill those gaps. He even predicted their properties. "He was right," said Scerri. "When new elements were discovered, they matched his predictions. It was a stunning vindication." Mendeleev was nominated for the Nobel Prize multiple times. He never won. "It's a mystery," said Scerri. "He should have won. He deserved to win." Mendeleev died in 1907. His periodic table is still used today. "It is one of the most important tools in chemistry," said Scerri. "His legacy is everywhere."`,
