    time: "Deep Dive",
    image: "https://imgs.mongabay.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2025/10/01230741/jane-goodall-HUGO-VAN-LAWICK.jpg",
    content: `In 1960, a 26-year-old woman named Jane Goodall arrived at Gombe Stream National Park in Tanzania. She had no degree. She had no training. She had a notebook and a passion for animals. "Goodall did something radical," said primatologist Dr. Frans de Waal. "She gave the chimpanzees names instead of numbers. She observed them as individuals. She discovered that they were more like us than anyone had imagined." Goodall observed chimps using tools — stripping leaves from twigs to fish for termites. Tool use was thought to be uniquely human. "It was a breakthrough," said de Waal. "Goodall had pushed back the boundary between humans and animals." She also observed chimps hunting, eating meat, and engaging in warfare. "They were not peaceful vegetarians," said de Waal. "They were complex beings with dark sides as well as light." Goodall's work revolutionized primatology. It also challenged the way humans think about animals. "She showed that we are not separate from nature," said de Waal. "We are part of it. That is a profound insight." Goodall is now in her 90s. She still travels the world, advocating for conservation and animal welfare. "She is a legend," said de Waal. "She changed the world."`,
