    image: "https://media.nbcwashington.com/2021/02/uss-katherine-johnson-Diptych-1.jpg?quality=85&strip=all&resize=1200%2C675",
    content: `Katherine Johnson was a mathematician at NASA. She calculated the trajectories for the first American in space, the first American in orbit, and the Apollo moon landing. "Johnson was a human computer," said historian Dr. Margot Lee Shetterly. "She did calculations that computers could not yet do. She was accurate. She was reliable. She was essential." In 1962, John Glenn was about to become the first American to orbit the Earth. He asked Johnson to double-check the computer's calculations. "If she says they're good, I'm ready to go," Glenn said. Johnson did the math. Glenn flew. "It was a moment of trust," said Shetterly. "Glenn trusted Johnson more than the machine." Johnson faced racism and sexism throughout her career. She was segregated from her white colleagues. She was paid less than men. "She did not complain," said Shetterly. "She worked. She excelled. She proved herself." Johnson was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 2015. She died in 2020 at the age of 101. "She was a pioneer," said Shetterly. "She broke barriers. She inspired generations."`,
